Technique: Multiple computed tomographic images of the abdomen and pelvis are presented for evaluation. Non-contrast axial, coronal and sagittal images are obtained.

Findings:
Sections through the lower lung fields show no pleuro-parenchymal abnormalities. Sections through the liver, spleen, pancreas and the adrenal glands appear normal in size and shape without focal abnormalities. Patient is status post cholecystectomy.

The kidneys appear normal in size. Simple appearing renal cysts are seen in both kidneys. The right kidney shows a 1.9 cm cyst in the upper pole and a 2.5 cm cyst in the lower pole. The left kidney shows a 5.7 cyst in the upper pole and two cysts in the lower pole; one measuring 1.5 cm in diameter and the second measuring 2.4 cm. 

A  5 mm non-obstructing calculus is seen in the cortex of the lower pole of right kidney. A vascular renal calcification is seen in the hilum of the right kidney, lower pole. A 12 mm non-obstructive calculus is seen in the lower pole of the left kidney.

There are mild atherosclerotic changes seen in the lower abdominal aorta.  Several phleboliths are seen in the lower pelvis. The prostate gland is prominent in size measuring 3.8 x 4.8 x 5.0 cm. The enlarged prostate gland mildly displaces the base of the bladder.  The visualized bony structures appear unremarkable.

IMPRESSION:
1. Bilateral simple appearing renal cysts as described above.  A Renal CT with Contrast is recommend for further evaluation, if clinically indicated.
2. Bilateral non-obstructed renal calcifications as described above.
3. Enlarged prostate gland ( 3.8 x 4.8 x 5.0 cm) mildly displacing the base of the bladder.
4. The patient is status post cholecystectomy.
5. Several small phleboliths are seen in the lower pelvis.
6. Mild atherosclerotic changes are seen in the lower abdominal aorta.

TECHNIQUE: 
Helical acquisition of CT data from the body of T10 through the sacrum. Sagittal and coronal reformations.

FINDINGS:
The most caudal well-formed disc space is L5-S1. There are 5 non-rib bearing lumbar spine .

Exaggerated lordotic curvature of the lumbar spine with grade 1 anterolisthesis at L4-5 without any evidence for pars defect. There is mild superior endplate deformity with small Schmorl's node at superior endplate of T12 and T11-T12 intervertebral disc space. Partially imaged bridging right anterolateral osteophytes along the lower thoracic spine There is marked endplate sclerosis and L4-5 and to a lesser degree along the posterior endplate of L5-S1 diffuse calcific atherosclerosis of the abdominal aorta with mild ectasia of the suprarenal abdominal aorta measuring up to 20 mm. The retroperitoneal structures are within normal limit . Degenerative changes of the bilateral SI joints with vacuum phenomenon and osteophytosis but with preserved joint spaces. There is suspicion for cortical step-off in the right sacral ala of S1, suspicious for incomplete fracture. Degenerative changes in the pubic symphysis joint. Moderate diverticulosis of the sigmoid colon desiccated mild burden of stool material identified in the rectum
Partially imaged lower hemithorax exhibits multiple peripheral emphysema/air cysts, mild reticulation and  bronchial wall thickening. 

T12-L1: No spinal canal or neural foraminal stenosis.

L1-L2: Mild facet arthropathy. Mild disc bulge. Minimal spinal canal narrowing. Mild bilateral neural foraminal stenosis.

L2-L3: Mild disc bulge and mild facet arthropathy with ligamentum flavum thickening. Minimal spinal canal narrowing and mild bilateral neural foraminal stenosis.

L3-L4: Mild disc bulge and moderate bilateral facet arthropathy with ligamentum flavum thickening. Mild spinal canal stenosis and moderate bilateral neural foraminal stenosis.

L4-L5: Moderate to severe bilateral facet arthropathy. Moderate to severe disc/osteophyte complex with vacuum phenomenon tracking into posterior aspect of the mid L5 vertebral body level, which may suggest extruded disc material. Ligamentum flavum thickening. At least moderate spinal canal stenosis attributable to ligamentum flavum thickening and dorsal osseous ridging of the posterior-superior corner of L5. Moderate to severe bilateral neural foraminal stenosis

L5-S1: Disc vacuum phenomenon. Moderate disc/osteophyte complex and moderate bilateral facet arthropathy. Ligamentum flavum thickening. No spinal canal stenosis. Moderate to severe bilateral neural foraminal stenosis

IMPRESSION:
 1) Multilevel degenerative lumbar spondylosis, most pronounced at L4-5 with grade 1 anterolisthesis, at least moderate spinal canal stenosis, and moderate to severe bilateral neural foraminal stenosis.
 2) Suspected extruded disc material at L4-5 with associated vacuum phenomenon extending posteriorly into the L5 vertebral body.
 3) Moderate to severe bilateral neural foraminal stenosis at L5-S1 without significant central canal stenosis.
 4) Mild spinal canal stenosis at L3-4 with moderate bilateral neural foraminal stenosis.
 5) Suspicion for incomplete fracture of the right sacral ala at S1; correlate with focal tenderness and consider further evaluation with MRI if clinically indicated.
 6) Degenerative changes of the bilateral sacroiliac joints and pubic symphysis.
 7) Incidental findings include mild suprarenal abdominal aortic ectasia (up to 20 mm), sigmoid diverticulosis, and partially imaged chronic interstitial lung changes and air cysts/emphsyema in the lower hemithorax.

TECHNIQUE:
Multidetector CT images of the chest were obtained without intravenous contrast. Multiplanar reformats and MIP imaging submitted.

FINDINGS:
Normal thyroid gland.

Mild emphysema.

Bandlike atelectasis in the right middle lobe and lingula.

IMPRESSION:
1. No acute cardiopulmonary process.
2. Mild emphysema.
3. No concerning pulmonary lesions.

TECHNIQUE:
MRI of the pelvis with and without IV contrast.

FINDINGS:
3.3 cm T2-hypointense well-defined round intramural fibroid at the uterine fundus. There is mild distortion of the underlying endometrial cavity, which appears otherwise normal. Subcentimeter physiological follicles in the right ovary.  Left ovary unremarkable.  Normal appearance of the urinary bladder.  Visualized lower lumbar spine and sacrum appear normal on the available images.

IMPRESSION:
Intramural fibroid in the uterine fundus measuring approximately 3.3 cm.

Technique: CT of the Abdomen and Pelvis without contrast.

Findings: Mild linear atelectasis or scars in the visualized lung bases. Mild cardiomegaly. Dysmorphic spleen with scattered parenchymal calcifications. Bilateral low and high attenuation renal cysts. 9 mm non obstructing calculus in the mid pole of the left kidney. Mild left hydronephrosis with moderate periureteral inflammatory fat stranding. No radiopaque obstructing calculus identified in the left ureter. Contracted urinary bladder. Prior colectomy with a right lower quadrant ileostomy. Moderate-sized fat- and small bowel-containing parastomal hernia without evidence of entrapment or obstruction. Inferior vena cava filter. Mild-to-moderate calcific atherosclerosis of the aortoiliac arterial system. Severe L3-L4 degenerative disc disease with grade 1 anterolisthesis of L3 on L4.

Impression: 
- Mild cardiomegaly.
- Mild left hydronephrosis with moderate periureteral inflammatory fat stranding. No radiopaque obstructing calculus identified in the left ureter. An obstructing mass or stricture is not seen in the distal left ureter, but cannot be excluded.

TECHNIQUE: Highâ€“resolution CT scan from the lung apices through the lung bases without IV contrast material. Axial, coronal and sagittal reconstructions obtained. 
 
FINDINGS:   
 
LUNGS AND AIRWAYS:  Right upper lobe calcified pulmonary granuloma measuring 0.7cm. Additional sub-centimeter calcified pulmonary granulomas. Scattered sub-segmental atelectasis. Osteophyte-induced adjacent pulmonary atelectasis and fibrosis in the right lower lobe. Right middle lobe bronchial dilation visualized on prone and supine imaging. 

MEDIASTINUM AND LYMPH NODES: Calcified mediastinal and right hilarity lymph nodes, largest measuring 1.3 cm.
 
PLEURA: No pleural effusion or pneumothorax. 
 
CARDIOVASCULAR: Heart is normal in size. Unremarkable pericardium. Coronary artery calcifications. Aortic arch calcifications. 
 
SOFT TISSUES AND BONES: No suspicious osseous lesion. No acute fracture.  Right humeral head surgical anchor. Productive bony change along the left humerus greater tubercle, may indicate chronic rotator cuff pathology. Multilevel spondylosis. 
 
UPPER ABDOMEN: Hepatosplenic calcified granulomata. 0.3 cm left renal calcification. Calcified lymph nodes near the GE junction and diaphragmatic crura.
 
 
IMPRESSION: 
 
Right middle lobe varicose bronchiectasis in addition to calcified pulmonary granulomas and mediastinal and right hilar calcified lymph nodes, suggestive of prior inflammatory or infectious process.

Technique:  Multiplanar multisequence MR imaging of the thoracic spine was obtained without intravenous contrast.

Findings:
Image quality is degraded by motion artifact.

Acute compression fracture of T11 with bone marrow edema and mild height loss.

Bone marrow edema in C7, concerning for compression fracture.

Chronic compression fracture of T12 with severe height loss.

Multilevel degenerative changes of the spine including disc desiccation, disc bulges, and facet arthropathy.  Findings are most severe in the lower thoracic spine with mild to moderate spinal canal and neuroforaminal narrowing.

Impression:
1.  Acute compression fracture of T11.
2. Edema of C7 may reflect compression fracture.  Dedicated C-spine MRI is recommended.
3. Chronic severe T12 compression fracture
4. Multilevel degenerative changes.

Technique: 
MDCT of the chest without intravenous contrast was obtained. Multiplanar reformats submitted. 

Findings: 
Lower neck and thyroid: within normal limits. 
Lungs: No focal consolidation or pulmonary edema. 5 mm ground glass nodule within the peripheral left lower lobe. Scattered areas of mosaic attenuation, which can be seen with small airway disease/air trapping. 
Airways: Patent. Diffuse smooth bronchial wall thickening. 
Pleura: No pneumothorax, focal thickening or pleural effusion. 
Heart: Normal size. No pericardial effusion. No detectable coronary artery calcifications. 
Vessels: Normal caliber ascending aorta and main pulmonary artery. 
Mediastinum: Within normal limits 
Lymph nodes: No axillary, hilar or mediastinal lymphadenopathy.
Chest wall: within normal limits. 
Bones: Old healed fracture of the left 7th rib. Otherwise, within normal limits. Preserved vertebral body heights. 
Upper abdomen: Visualized liver, pancreas, adrenal glands, kidneys, stomach and spleen are within normal limits. 

Impression: 
Scattered areas of mosaic attenuation and mild diffuse bronchial wall thickening. Findings can be seen with bronchitis or reactive airways disease. 

Left lower lobe 5 mm ground glass nodule, per Fleischner society guidelines, no follow up is recommended.

Technique: CTA of the Abdomen and Pelvis.

Findings: Mild calcific atherosclerosis of the aortoiliac arterial system. No abdominal aortic aneurysm. 1.5 cm right hepatic cyst. 1.2 cm cyst in hepatic segment 6. 1.3 cm low attenuation lesion in the mid pole of the right kidney. Mild prostatomegaly. Colonic diverticulosis. Right total hip arthroplasty. Moderate left hip degenerative joint disease.

Impression: 
- No abdominal aortic aneurysm.
- Mild calcific atherosclerosis of the aortoiliac arterial system. 
- 1.3 cm low attenuation lesion in the mid pole of the right kidney, possibly a cyst. A renal ultrasound or MRI may provide additional characterization, if clinically warranted. 
- Prostatomegaly

TECHNIQUE: MRI of the lumbar spine was performed utilizing sagittal T1, T2 FR FSE, stir, axial PD, axial T1, axial T2 sequences. 

FINDINGS:

Alignment: 3-4 mm retrolisthesis demonstrated at L2-3 and 2-3 mm retrolisthesis at L3-4. 

L1-2: Mild disc height loss.  Small anterior discogenic osteophytes.  2 mm concentric disc bulge posterior portion of which indents the ventral thecal sac.  T2 hyperintense focus posterior right central disc annulus consistent with a small annular fissure.  Mild hypertrophy of the facet joints with redundancy of ligamentum flavum.  Central canal diameter is normal.  Lateral recesses are patent.  Mild bilateral foraminal stenosis. 

L2-3: Moderate disc height loss.  Small anterior discogenic osteophytes with reactive endplate fat.  Mild retrolisthesis.  2-3 mm posterior disc bulge indents the ventral thecal sac with foraminal encroachment.  Mild hypertrophy of the facet joints with redundancy of ligamentum flavum.  Central canal diameter is normal.  There is mild narrowing of the right subarticular recess.  Moderate bilateral foraminal stenosis. 

L3-4: Normal disc height.  2-3 mm retrolisthesis.  3-4 mm posterior disc bulge indents the ventral thecal sac and encroaches on the foramina.  Moderate hypertrophy of the facet joints with redundancy of ligamentum flavum.  Combination of factors results in severe stenosis of the spinal canal and lateral recess.  There may be impingement of the traversing L4 nerve roots.  Severe foraminal stenosis with suspected impingement of the exiting L3 nerve roots bilaterally. 

L4-5: Mild disc height loss.  Concentric disc bulge with discogenic osteophytes, asymmetrically largest toward the left foraminal zone measuring up to 4-5 mm with reactive endplate fat.  Moderate hypertrophy of the facet joints with redundancy of ligamentum flavum.  Combination of factors results in severe stenosis of the spinal canal and lateral recess.  There may be impingement of traversing L5 nerve roots.  Severe bilateral foraminal stenosis, worse on the left.  Suspect impingement of exiting L4 nerve roots. 

L5-S1: Normal disc height.  Broad-based 2 mm posterior left subarticular disc protrusion with small annular fissure encroaching on the left lateral recess.  Moderate hypertrophy of the facet joints with redundancy of ligamentum flavum.  Normal central canal diameter.  Patent lateral recess.  No foraminal stenosis. 

IMPRESSION:
Multilevel degenerative spondylosis.

TECHNIQUE:
Multidetector CT images of the abdomen and pelvis were obtained after the administration of intravenous and oral contrast.  Multiplanar reformats.

FINDINGS:
Cirrhotic liver morphology with tiny subcentimeter indeterminate liver lesion identified.

The spleen is normal in size.

The pancreas and adrenal glands demonstrate a normal appearance.

15 mm left simple bosniak type I renal cyst.  Additional 12 mm exophytic right renal simple cyst.

There is contrast within the bowel which is nonobstructed.

Large volume ascites.

Anasarca and skin thickening in the lower anterior subcutaneous soft tissue.

Metallic surgical hardware in the left proximal femur.

Gallbladder not visualized.

Multilevel moderate degenerative disc disease with vacuum disc phenomenon.

The prostate is moderately enlarged and impinges posteriorly on the urinary bladder.

The urinary bladder is unremarkable.

IMPRESSION:
1. Cirrhotic liver morphology with sequela of portal hypertension including large volume ascites.
2. Normal spleen size.
3. Indeterminate subcentimeter low denisty liver lesion.  Consider MRI abdomen with and without contrast for further assessment.

Technique: CT of the Chest with contrast and CT of the Abdomen and Pelvis pre- and post-IV contrast administration.

Findings: Moderate bronchial wall thickening with mild-to-moderate cystic bronchiectasis and scattered mucus plugs, predominantly involving the right middle lobe, lingula and lower lobes. Associated scattered and clustered micro nodules. Small volume of secretions in the mid and distal trachea. Subcentimeter left renal cyst. Focal cortical thinning involving the posterior mid-to-upper pole of the left kidney. Mild colonic diverticulosis. L4-L5 fusion hardware.

Impression: 
- Moderate bronchial wall thickening with mild-to-moderate cystic bronchiectasis, mucous plugs, and scattered/clustered micro nodules, predominantly involving the right middle lobe, lingula and, less so, the lower lobes. These findings can be seen in mycobacterium avian complex or other infectious or inflammatory etiologies.
- Focal cortical thinning involving the posterior mid-to-upper pole of the left kidney, possibly related to a prior partial nephrectomy.

TECHNIQUE: MRI of the lumbar spine utilizing sagittal T1, axial PD FSE MSMA, axial T2 FRFSE MSMA, sagittal T2 FRFSE, sagittal PD FSE, and axial T1

FINDINGS:
Numbering is based on the presumption of 5 lumbar type vertebral bodies.

Lumbar vertebral body height is preserved. There is no subluxation.  Vertebral marrow signal is within normal limits. Tiny Schmorl's nodes are seen in the superior endplates of L2 and L4.

The conus ends at T12-L1.

T12-L1: No spinal canal stenosis or neural foramen narrowing. 

L1-L2: No spinal canal stenosis or neural foramen narrowing. 

L2-L3: No spinal canal stenosis or neural foramen narrowing. 

L3-L4:  Mild disc desiccation. No spinal canal stenosis or neural foramen narrowing. 

L4-L5: No spinal canal stenosis or neural foramen narrowing. 

L5-S1: Mild disc desiccation. Minor broad disc bulge with osteophytic ridging in the neural foramina. No associated spinal canal stenosis. Mild right neural foramen narrowing.

IMPRESSION:
Minor broad disc bulge at L5-S1 with mild right neural foramen narrowing.

TECHNIQUE: Multiplanar, multiecho MRI of the brain performed including axial FLAIR, axial gradient, sagittal T1, axial T2, axial T1, axial diffusion and coronal T2 weighted images. No contrast.

FINDINGS:

DIFFUSION:  Negative for acute stroke.    
 
BRAIN PARENCHYMA AND EXTRA-AXIAL SPACES:  Severe bilateral white matter T2 signal hyperintensities. Moderate global volume loss. Normal morphology of the corpus callosum. No Chiari malformation. Empty sella. Preserved intracranial flow voids.  Negative for hemorrhage.

MASTOIDS, ORBITS AND PARANASAL SINUSES:   Bilateral cataract surgeries. Small left maxillary sinus mucous retention cysts.

IMPRESSION:
1. Negative for acute stroke.

2. Severe chronic small vessel ischemic disease.

3. Moderate global volume loss.

4. Empty sella. This is frequently a finding without clinical consequence. It can also be seen with idiopathic intracranial hypertension (considered unlikely) or pituitary dysfunction.

Technique:  CT abdomen and pelvis with IV and oral contrast, including coronal and sagittal reformats.

Findings:
Lower thorax:  Lung bases are clear.  Trace pericardial effusion.

Hepatobiliary:  No focal hepatic lesions.  Normal gallbladder.

Pancreas:  No acute abnormality.

Spleen:  Nonspecific 4mm irregular ill-defined hypodensity, likely benign.

Adrenal:  No acute abnormality.

Kidneys:  Upper pole renal cortical scarring bilaterally.  No hydronephrosis.  Symmetric renal enhancement and excretion.

Gastrointestinal:  Short segment wall thickening of proximal to mid sigmoid colon with inflammatory fat stranding about several diverticula.  No adjacent abscess or free air.  Colonic diverticulosis.

Pelvic organs:  Sigmoid inflammation extends to the adjacent left ovary, which is mildly enlarged and enhancing.  Lobulated 2.1 x 1.7 x 2.4 cm cystic lesion in the right anterior pelvis may reflect a right ovarian follicular cyst.  Hysterectomy.

Bladder:  Sigmoid inflammation extends to the adjacent left superior bladder.  No bladder wall thickening or intraluminal gas.

Lymph nodes:  Multiple subcentimeter lymph nodes in the bilateral inguinal regions.

Vascular:  No acute abnormality.

Bone and soft tissue:  Mild degenerative changes of the spine.  Grade 1 anterolisthesis L4 on L5.

Impression:
1.  Acute sigmoid diverticulitis in the left lower quadrant with inflammation of the adjacent left ovary.  

2.  Sigmoid inflammation extends to the adjacent superior bladder, however no evidence for colovesicular fistula.

Indication: None

Technique: Routine MR of the thoracic spine was performed, including sagittal T1, T2, STIR and axial T2 weighted sequences.

Findings:

Preserved bone marrow signal of the thoracic vertebral column.  

Multilevel disc dessication. 

Small left central disc protrusion at T5-6 which slightly indents the left ventral thecal sac. 

Central disc protrusion at T7-8 which slight indents the ventral cord resulting in moderate spinal canal stenosis. 

No cord signal abnormality.

No neuroforaminal narrowing.


Impression: 

Central disc protrusion in the mid thoracic spine at T7-8 which indents the ventral cord, resulting in moderate spinal canal stenosis.

Additional smaller left central disc herniation two levels higher in the mid thoracic spine at T5-6, which slightly indents the left ventral thecal sac without spinal canal stenosis. 

No cord edema.

No neural foraminal narrowing.

Technique: 
CT chest was obtained from the jugular notch through the posterior costophrenic recess without IV contrast. Coronal and sagittal reformats as well as 3D MIPS reconstruction. 


FINDINGS:

Lungs/Pleura: There is peripheral traction bronchiectasis in the bilateral lungs and signal abnormality without convincing apico-basal gradient and most accentuated in the left upper lobe. There is patchy microcystic honeycombing identified in the left upper lobe and bibasilar lungs. Airway is patent. There is a 5 mm juxta fissural nodule in the right upper lobe, favored to represent intrapulmonary lymph node. A 3 mm sized nodule in the apical left upper lobe. There is very mild heterogeneous attenuation of the lung parenchyma, given absence of the expiratory acquisition but may represent small airway disease. No pleural effusion. No pneumothorax.

Axilla/Soft Tissue: No supraclavicular or axillary adenopathy. No evidence for large breast mass.

Mediastinum: No pathologic mediastinal or hilar adenopathy.  The esophagus is within normal limit.

Heart/Aorta: Scant pericardial effusion. No coronary artery calcifications.

Upper Abdomen:
Status post cholecystectomy. A 2.3 cm sized hypodensity in the hepatic segment 7, most commonly seen with hepatic cyst. Calcific granulomata in the spleen

Bones:
No evidence of fracture, dislocation, or aggressive osseous abnormality. Osteopenia.

IMPRESSION:
 1) Peripheral traction bronchiectasis with associated fibrotic change and patchy microcystic honeycombing involving the bilateral lungs, most pronounced in the left upper lobe, without a convincing apico-basal gradient. Findings are compatible with chronic fibrotic lung disease.
 2) Scattered small pulmonary nodules, including a 5 mm juxta-fissural right upper lobe nodule favored to represent an intrapulmonary lymph node and a 3 mm left apical upper lobe nodule. Recommend follow-up per Fleischner Society guidelines, if clinically indicated.
 3) Very mild heterogeneous lung attenuation, possibly reflecting small airway disease, noting absence of expiratory imaging.
 4) Status post cholecystectomy with an approximately 2.3 cm hepatic segment VII cyst. Calcified splenic granulomata.

TECHNIQUE:  A noncontrast CT of the chest was performed including thin, high resolution axial slices through lungs as well as MIP reconstructed images.  


FINDINGS:

Scattered lucencies and cystic spaces are appreciated in an upper lung and subpleural distribution consistent with mild paraseptal emphysema.  

A small hiatal hernia is present.  Moderate calcific atherosclerosis of the thoracic and upper abdominal aorta is appreciated.  Dense coronary calcifications are noted.  Mild degenerative osteoarthritis is appreciated in the thoracic spine with prominent anterior osteophytes and disc space narrowing throughout the thoracic spine.  

Cholelithiasis is appreciated.  A calcified stone is noted at the lower pole of the right renal collecting system.  Multiple, low density cystic lesions are appreciated in the right lobe of the liver.  Cysts are appreciated posteriorly at the upper pole, anteriorly in the mid left kidney, and posterolaterally at the lower pole of the left kidney.   


IMPRESSION:

1.  Mild paraseptal emphysema.  

2.  Indeterminate low density liver lesions may be further characterized with an ultrasound or MRI.

3.  Left renal cysts.

4.  Nephrolithiasis.

5.  Cholelithiasis

Technique: MRI of the cervical spine consisting of localizer sequences, sagittal T2 weighted sequences, sagittal T1 weighted sequences, sagittal STIR sequences, and axial T2 star sequences. The exam is degraded by motion artifact.

Findings:
Mild straightening of the normal cervical lordosis. Mild Modic type 1 endplate changes at C3/4. No aggressive osseous lesions. No cord signal abnormality. Craniocervical junction intact. Limited assessment of the posterior fossa is unremarkable. Limited assessment to the paraspinal soft tissues unremarkable.

C2-3: Mild disc building with facet and uncovertebral hypertrophy. No spinal canal narrowing. Foramina are not well assessed due to artifact but question mild bilateral foraminal stenosis. 

C3-4: Disc osteophyte complex with facet and uncovertebral hypertrophy. Moderate spinal canal stenosis.  Foramina are not well assessed due to artifact but question moderate bilateral foraminal stenosis.

C4-5: Disc bulge with facet and uncovertebral hypertrophy. No spinal canal narrowing (best visualized on the sagittal plane). Foramina are not well assessed due to artifact but question moderate to severe bilateral foraminal stenosis.

C5-6: Disc osteophyte complex with facet and uncovertebral hypertrophy. Mild spinal canal stenosis.  Foramina are not well assessed due to artifact but question moderate severe left and mild to moderate right foraminal stenosis.

C6-7:  Diffuse disc bulge with a broad left paracentral protrusion which mildly deforms the ventral cord without overall canal stenosis. Facets maintained. No neural foraminal stenosis.

C7-T1: Disc and facets maintained. No spinal canal or foraminal stenosis.

Impression:
1. Multilevel degenerative changes.
2. Moderate canal stenosis at C3-C4.
3. Varying degrees of foraminal stenosis up to moderate severe as outlined in the findings section.

Technique: MR spine without intravenous contrast, including Sagittal and axial T1 and T2 sequences and Sagittal STIR sequences

Findings:

Alignment: The normal lumbar lordosis is maintained. Grade 1 anterolisthesis of L4 on L5. Mild retrolisthesis of L2 on L3 and L1 on L2.

Vertebral bodies: Status post screw and rod fixation of L3 and L4 vertebral bodies. Osseous signal is maintained. Vertebral body heights are maintained. No acute fracture. Type 2 Modic changes at L5/S1 level. Multilevel facet arthropathy.

Disc: status post disc spacer at L3/L4. Multilevel intervertebral disc space height loss and disc desiccation, severe at L5/S1 and L1/L2, and moderate at L4/L5 and L2/L3. Broad based disc bulges at L2/L3 and L1/L2

Foramen/Spine: Mild bilateral L1/L2 and L2/L3 neuroforamen stenosis. Moderate spinal canal stenosis at L1/L2-L2/L3 secondary to disc bulge and facet arthropathy.

Cord: Normal cord signal

Soft tissues: Normal paravertebral soft tissues. Bilateral T2 bright, T1 dark renal cyst measuring up to 5.5 cm

Impression:
No acute pathology

Multilevel degenerative changes as described above

TECHNIQUE:
Axial, coronal and sagittal CT images of the chest were obtained without contrast media

FINDINGS:
LOWER NECK AND AXILLA: Negative for lymphadenopathy. 

HEART AND VESSELS: Heart size is large.
Negative for pericardial effusion.
There is dilatation of the ascending aorta measuring 4.6 cm diameter. There is multivessel coronary artery calcification. There are moderate valvular calcifications. There is atherosclerotic calcification of the aorta. Negative for pericardial effusion.

 MEDIASTINUM AND HILA: Negative for lymphadenopathy.

 LUNG AND AIRWAYS
There are trace mucosal secretions within the tracheal lumen.
There is emphysema.
There is a 5 mm pulmonary nodule in the posterior aspect of the left lower lobe. 

PLEURA: Negative for pleural effusion or pneumothorax. 

ESOPHAGUS: Unremarkable. 

THORACIC BONES AND CHEST WALL: There is chronic 20% height loss superior endplate compression deformity in the T7 vertebral body.

UPPER ABDOMEN : There is chronic calcification of the right adrenal gland. Negative for acute abnormality within the visualized portion of the upper abdomen.

IMPRESSION:
1. Emphysema with 5mm left lower lobe pulmonary nodule.  Given the underlying emphysema, recommend follow up low dose CT lung cancer screening or CT chest in 12 months.
2. Cardiomegaly
3. Multivessel coronary artery calcification

TECHNIQUE:
Multidetector CT images of the abdomen submitted before and after the administration of intravenous contrast.  Multiplanar reformats.

FINDINGS:
Markedly enlarged fibroid uterus.

Mild right and mild left hydronephrosis likely related to compression from large fibroid uterus.

No urolithiasis or solid renal parenchymal lesion.

Gastroplasty changes.

IMPRESSION:
1. Large multi-fibroid uterus most resulting in mild bilateral hydronephrosis.
2. No urolithiasis, renal parenchymal lesion, or uroepithelial lesion.

TECHNIQUE:
Chest CT without contrast.

FINDINGS:    

Lungs:  1.0 cm solid right upper lobe nodule.

0.9 cm solid right middle lobe nodule.

0.3 cm solid right middle lobe nodule

1.0 cm solid right middle lobe nodule

2.7 cm solid medial right lower lobe nodule

Mild left basilar atelectasis or scarring. Mild elevation of the left hemidiaphragm. Minimal right basilar scarring or atelectasis.

Upper abdomen/soft tissues: Multiple non pathologically enlarged left and right axillary lymph nodes. 

Mediastinum/Pleura: Moderate pericardial effusion measures 19 Hounsfield units; simple fluid. Mild cardiomegaly. Mild coronary calcium.  

Severe mitral annular calcification. The main pulmonary artery measures 3.9 cm. Mild aortic atherosclerotic vascular calcification.

Mildly enlarged right paratracheal lymph node measures 1.1 cm in short axis. Mildly enlarged lymph node anterior to the carina measures 1.4 cm in short axis.    
 
Bones:  Old left sixth rib fracture. Spinal degenerative changes.      

IMPRESSION:
1. Multiple right lung nodules suspicious for neoplasm. Fungal infection, rheumatoid nodules or granulomatosis with polyangiitis possible as well but statistically less likely.

2. Mildly enlarged mediastinal lymph nodes could be reactive or neoplastic.

3. Moderate pericardial effusion.

4. Mild coronary artery calcium. This is a marker of coronary atherosclerosis.

5. Mild cardiomegaly.

6. Severe mitral annular calcification. This can be seen with clinically significant valve disease. Correlate with echo.

7. Main pulmonary artery diameter exceeding 3 cm suggests pulmonary arterial hypertension.

Technique: Non-contrast CT of the brain 

Findings: Small acute subdural hematoma over the left frontal lobe, measuring up to 3 mm in thickness. No acute transcortical infarction. No midline shift or herniation. 

Chronic lacunar infarcts in the bilateral gangliocapsular regions and thalami. 

Probably chronic ischemic changes of the white matter, moderate in extent. Atherosclerotic calcifications of the carotid siphons. 

Mild cerebral atrophy with proportional ventricular enlargement. 

Bilateral lens replacement. Partial opacification of the partially visualized maxillary sinuses bilaterally, left more so than right.

Impression:
 
Small acute subdural hematoma over the left frontal lobe measuring up to 3 mm in thickness. No midline shift or herniation.

TECHNIQUE: Multiple axial, coronal and sagittal MR sequences of the pelvis were obtained with and without intravenous contrast.   

FINDINGS: 
Circumscribed, thin-walled, unilocular non-enhancing right ovarian cyst following fluid signal on all sequences measures  4.9 x 3.9 x 4.9 cm. The left ovary is not visualized. Status post hysterectomy.  No pathologic lymph nodes. No free fluid. The bladder is normal. Small fat-containing umbilical hernia. Sigmoid diverticulosis. Degenerative changes of the bilateral hips. No suspicious osseous lesion. 

IMPRESSION:
Simple 4.9 cm right ovarian cyst

INDCATION: Hemangioma, Ovarian cyst

TECHNIQUE: MRI of the bony pelvis was performed without and with contrast. 

FINDINGS:  There is a 5 x 8 x 9 mm focus along the right lateral margin of L5 vertebral body which demonstrates peripheral T1 hypointensity with central hyperintensiy. There is corresponding hyperintensity on the STIR and FS sequences. Following contrast administration, the lesion demonstrates avid enhancement. 

The remaining marrow signal intensity is maintained.  The sacrum appears unremarkable with no evidence of sacral stress fracture. The sacroiliac joint appears unremarkable. Symphysis pubis is unremarkable.  Degenerative changes of the lower lumbar spine.

Both the femoral heads are unremarkable without evidence of marrow edema, avascular necrosis or fracture. There is mild L4-L5 disc desiccation with a disc protrusion/annular tear resulting in mild spinal canal narrowing.  No significant neuroforaminal stenosis identified in the imaged lower lumbar spine. 

The uterus and the endometrium are normal in morphology and signal intensity.  No cystic or solid adnexa mass noted. 

The imaged muscles demonstrate normal muscle bulk and signal intensity. 

IMPRESSION: 
1. Subcentimeter focus along the right lateral margin of L5 vertebral body with signal characteristic most consistent with an intraosseous hemangioma. 
2. No cystic or solid adnexa mass.

Technique: Multiple computed tomographic images of the abdomen and pelvis are presented for evaluation. Non-contrast multiplanar images are obtained.

Findings:
Section through the lower chest show a moderate cardiomegaly. A moderate sized right pleural effusion is also seen.  A moderate amount of ascites is seen in the abdomen and extending into the pelvis. Several small gallstones are seen in the gallbladder. Scattered small calcification are seen in the spleen consistent with calcified granulomatous residuals. The liver, pancreas, kidneys and adrenal glands show no focal abnormalities; although, lack of IV contrast limits evaluation. 
 
Sections through the pelvis show a small non-distended bladder containing urine. The pelvis structures are not well seen due to the ascites. Specifically, the uterus and ovaries are not well seen. There a few scattered phleboliths seen in the lower pelvis. A well circumscribed low attenuating mass is seen in the right inner thigh  at the level of the right vulva. It has a CT number of -100 Hounsfield units. It measures 6.5 cm in AP diameter x 5.6 cm in transverse diameter x at least 3.5 cm in height.   The CT scan truncates the inferior border of this mass. This likely represents a small benign lipoma. The bony spine show a mild grade 1 anterolisthesis is seen involving the L5 vertebra with respect to S1.   Severe degenerative narrowing and vacuum phenomenon is present at L5-S1.  No spondylolysis is seen. 

IMPRESSION:
1. Moderate cardiomegaly.
2. Moderate right pleural effusion is seen.
3. A moderate amount of ascites is seen in the abdomen extending into the dependent portions of the pelvis.
4. Cholelithiasis.
5. Calcified granulomatous residuals are seen in the spleen.
6. There is poor visualization of the the pelvic structures especially the ovaries and uterus. Recommend a pelvic sonogram for further evaluation.
7. Scattered small phleboliths are seen in the lower pelvis. 
8. A mass is seen in right inner thigh at the level of the right vulva as described above likely representing a benign lipoma. Further evaluation with Ultrasound may be helpful.
9. A mild grade 1 anterolisthesis is seen involving the L5 vertebra with respect to S1. Severe degenerative changes are seen at the L5-S1 level. No obvious spondylolysis is seen.

TECHNIQUE: 
Contiguous axial CT sections were acquired through the chest without the use of IV contrast.  Coronal and sagittal reformatted images were created.

There is a 0.3 cm calcified granuloma in the lingula.  There is a 0.2 cm calcified granuloma in the superior segment of the left lower lobe.  There is a 0.2 cm calcified granuloma in the periphery of the right upper lobe.

There are coronary artery calcifications.

There is a small focus of calcific tendinitis adjacent to the right humeral head.  Mild degeneration is noted in the spine.

Scattered punctate calcified granulomas in the lungs. 

Calcific atherosclerosis including coronary artery calcification.

Technique: Axial, Coronal and Sagittal CTA images of the abdomen and pelvis with IV contrast

Findings:
Liver: The liver is normal in size and contour. No masses.
Spleen: Normal in size. Inhomogeneous enhancement is most likely physiological and transient.
Pancreas: No masses or adjacent inflammation.
Gallbladder/biliary system: Normal gallbladder. No abnormal biliary dilation.
Adrenals: Normal right adrenal gland. Indeterminate 0.7 x 1.2 cm left adrenal nodule.
Kidneys: Symmetric perfusion. No hydronephrosis. No obstructing renal stones. No solid renal mass. 2.8 x 2.5 cm right interpolar region simple renal cyst.
Bowel: Small hiatal hernia. No abnormal small bowel dilation. No acute colonic pathology.
Mesentery: No mesenteric mass. No pneumoperitoneum. No Ascites
Lymph nodes: No abnormal lymph nodes.
Vasculature: 4.6 x 4.1 x 4.5 cm (AP x TR x CC) fusiform infrarenal aortic aneurysm with mural thrombus resulting in a 3.3 x 2.8 cm lumen. The Inferior mesenteric artery arises from the aneurysmal sac. 1.9x 1.6 cm distal left common iliac artery aneurysm. There is diffuse atherosclerosis.
Pelvis: The bladder is under-distended. There is a fibroid uterus. No adnexal mass.
Bones: status post left hip arthroplasty. Moderate degenerative changes of the spine. No acute fractures.
Lungs/Chest: There are bilateral dependent areas of atelectasis. There is mosaic attenuation and moderate centrilobular emphysematous changes. There is a 3 mm right middle lobe nodule and 1.1 cm left lingula nodule. Mild cardiomegaly.

Impression: 
No acute abdominopelvic pathology.
Infrarenal aortic aneurysm measuring up to 4.6 cm, as well as a 1.9 cm left common iliac aneurysm. Recommend non-emergent follow-up with vascular surgery and follow-up cross-sectional imaging in 6 months to a year.
Indeterminate 1.2 cm left adrenal mass, follow-up with adrenal CT or MRI on a non-emergent/outpatient basis is recommended.
Emphysematous changes of the lungs with evidence of small airway disease.
Bilateral pulmonary nodules. Recommend dedicated CT chest imaging on a non-emergent/outpatient basis.

Technique: Multiplanar, multisequence MRI of the abdomen was performed before and after administration of intravenous contrast.

FINDINGS:

0.7 cm benign simple right renal cyst.

Technique:  Multiplanar, multi-sequence lumbar spine MRI.  No contrast.  

Findings:  Infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm measures approximately 4.4 in AP dimension and 4.7 cm in craniocaudal extent when measured in the sagittal plane.   It is not well assessed in the axial plane due to technique.

Infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm.   Recommend CTA.

TECHNIQUE:  Multi-planar, multi-sequence MRI of the lumbar spine without contrast. 


FINDINGS:

The lumbar spine is well aligned.  The L2 vertebral body is high signal on T1 and T2 images and does not completely suppress on fat suppression images.  The signal characteristics in the T2 vertebral body are most consistent with an atypical or vascular hemangioma.  However, comparison with any prior studies and interval follow-up are recommended to ensure stability.  Mild intervertebral disc space narrowing is noted at T12 - L1 and L4 - L5.  No abnormal cord signal is present.  The conus is located at the T12 - L1 interspace.  


T12 - L1:  No significant stenosis is appreciated.

L1 - L2:  No significant stenosis is appreciated. 

L2 - L3:  Facet arthropathy causes mild narrowing of the thecal sac and mild right neuroforaminal stenosis. 

L3 - L4:  A broad based disc bulge, facet arthropathy and thickening of the ligamentum flavum cause mild narrowing of the thecal sac, mild right and mild left neuroforaminal stenosis. 

L4 - L5:  A right asymmetric broad based disc bulge and facet arthropathy cause moderate narrowing of the thecal sac, moderate to marked right and mild to moderate left neuroforaminal stenosis.  

L5 - S1:  No significant stenosis is present.  

IMPRESSION:

1.  Multilevel degenerative changes in the lumbar spine most marked at the L4 - L5 interspace with moderate to marked right neuroforaminal stenosis and moderate narrowing of the thecal sac.

2.  Atypical, vascular hemangioma versus indeterminate lesion in the L2 vertebral body.  Comparison with prior images and interval follow-up is recommended.

2. Bilateral pleural effusions, right greater than left, and mild interstitial pulmonary edema.

Left upper lobe 3mm nodule. Left pleural based 5mm nodule. 12 month follow up chest CT may be considered based on patient risk factors.

FINDINGS: Pulmonary emphysema.  There is a perifissural nodule, along the minor fissure, of doubtful clinical significance.  Calcified granuloma within the lingula.  Dependent atelectasis. Calcified splenic granuloma.  Splenule.

4. Coronary artery calcifications.
5. Tiny flash filling hepatic hemangioma.

Impression:

Multilevel cervical spondylosis, with mild cord compression at both C3-4 and C5-6. No cord signal abnormality.

No listhesis. Nonspecific straightening of the cervical lordosis.

Technique: Multiplanar multisequence MRI of the cervical spine was performed without contrast. 

Findings:
At C5-6 there is mild disc bulge with a superimposed large right foraminal extrusion with likely impingement of the right C6 nerve root. This mildly deforms the ventral cord with mild canal stenosis. No cord signal abnormality. Severe right foraminal stenosis. 

Multilevel degenerative changes noted elsewhere in the cervical spine. Paraspinal soft tissues unremarkable. 

Impression:
1. At C5-6 there is large right foraminal extrusion with likely impingement of the right C6 nerve root. Mild associated canal stenosis.
2. Multilevel degenerative changes elsewhere.

TECHNIQUE:
Multiplanar multisequence MRI sequences obtained before and after the administration of intravenous contrast.

FINDINGS:
Cirrhotic liver morphology.  Large focus of scarring and indentation at the hepatic dome.

3.0 cm T1 hyperintense lesion in segment 8 demonstrating no significant T2 hyperintensity.  This focus does not demonstrate diffusion restriction.

Numerous tiny T2 hyperintense cystic lesions throughout the pancreas.

IMPRESSION:
Cirrhotic liver morphology with a treated lesion in segment 8 likely related to ablation changes.  
No evidence of residual enhancement to suggest recurrent disease.

Technique:  
Sagittal and axial MRI sequences of the lumbar spine without IV contrast

Findings:  
There are magnetic susceptibility artifacts consistent with bilateral pedicle screws at the levels of L4-S1. The conus medullaris is at the level of L2. Multilevel disc protrusions, associated with variable degrees of spinal canal narrowing. These are most marked at L3-L4, where a disc bulge and bilateral facet hypertrophy result in moderate to severe spinal canal narrowing at this level. There is also severe bilateral neuroforaminal narrowing at this level. Grade 1 anterolisthesis of L4 with associated pars defects.

Impression:
Disc bulge and facet hypertrophy at the level of L3-4 resulting in moderate to severe spinal canal narrowing and severe bilateral neuroforaminal narrowing at this level.

TECHNIQUE:
Multidetector CT images of the chest were obtained without intravenous contrast.  

FINDINGS:
Right middle lobe collapse with air bronchograms noted.  

Cylindrical bronchiectasis of the lingula.

IMPRESSION:
1. Complete right middle lobe collapse.  
2. Mild cylindrical bronchiectasis of the lingula.

Technique: Multiplanar, Multisequence MRI of the lumbar spine without intravenous contrast

Findings:
There is partial lumbarization of S1. There is a broad-based disc bulge at L5/S1 with a small left subarticular disc protrusion and annular fissure creating mild spinal stenosis and moderate left sided neuroforaminal stenosis. There is compression of the emerging left S1 nerve root.  Additionally, there is mild central endplate depression throughout the visualized spine.

Impression:

L5-S1 disc bulge with small left subarticular disc herniation and annular fissure compresses the emerging left S1 nerve root.  There is mild spinal canal stenosis and moderate left neuroforaminal stenosis.

TECHNIQUE: 
Multiplanar multisequence MRI of the abdomen without contrast.

FINDINGS:
There is moderate ascites. Mildly nodular contour to liver, compatible with cirrhosis.

IMPRESSION:
Moderate ascites.

Technique: CT of the Chest, Abdomen, and Pelvis with IV contrast.

Findings: 4.7 x 3.2 cm ill-defined mass versus dense tissue or fluid in the left breast. Mild-to-moderate atelectasis in the lingula and lower lobes. Moderate-to-severe coronary artery calcifications. Normal liver and spleen. 1.5 cm fat attenuation lesion in the 1st portion of the duodenum. Prior cholecystectomy. Mild nodular hyperplasia of the left adrenal gland. Duplicated left renal collecting system. Foley catheter within the urinary bladder. Calcified uterine fibroids. Suspected 4.5 x 3.9 cm ill-defined soft tissue mass in the rectum. Severe calcific atherosclerosis of the aortoiliac and visualized femoral arterial system. Moderate degenerative disc disease of the thoracolumbar spine. Partial fusion of the L3 and L4 vertebral bodies. Acute or subacute fracture deformities of the left lateral 2nd, 3rd, 4th, 7th, and 10th ribs.

Impression: 
- Suspected 4.5 x 3.9 cm ill-defined soft tissue mass in the rectum. Malignancy cannot be excluded and further evaluation is recommended.
- 4.7 x 3.2 cm ill-defined mass versus dense tissue or fluid in the left breast. A left breast ultrasound or MRI may provide additional characterization, if clinically warranted.
- Moderate-to-severe coronary artery calcifications. 
- 1.5 cm lipoma in the 1st portion of the duodenum. 
- Acute or subacute fracture deformities of the left lateral 2nd, 3rd, 4th, 7th, and 10th ribs.

MRI ABDOMEN 

Technique: Multiplanar, multisequence MR imaging acquired through the abdomen.  Pre-gadolinium and post gadolinium imaging acquired.
  
Findings: 
The liver is enlarged measuring up to 23.5 cm in craniocaudad length.

Diffuse parenchymal steatosis of the liver as evidenced by significant diffuse uniform signal dropout of the hepatic parenchyma on out of phase sequence as compared to in phase sequence relative to body wall musculature.

No abdominal ascites.

No intrahepatic or extrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation.  Common bile duct measures up to 4 mm diameter.

Small 2.1 cm apparent lesion in the pancreatic tail which is most conspicuously appreciated on T1 fat-sat post gadolinium images as centrally hypointense with questionable thin rim enhancement.  The lesion is subtly hyperintense on T2-weighted series, but is noted to demonstrate significant loss of signal on T2 fat sat series.  Overall, the finding predominantly follows fat signal intensity on multiple sequences including DWI series.

Small 9 mm T2 hyperintense upper pole cyst in the left kidney.

 
IMPRESSION:
1.  Hepatomegaly with diffuse parenchymal steatosis.
2.  Small 2.1 cm lesion in the pancreatic tail which appears to follow fat signal intensity on multiple sequences as described.  Although relatively uncommon, could consider a small pancreatic lipoma.  Volume averaging with focally invaginated retroperitoneal fat is felt to be less likely based on morphology.  Rim-enhancing malignancy such as pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor is also felt to be less likely.  However, suggest clinical workup in this regard with consideration of appropriate nuclear imaging imaging if indicated.  Short-term cross-sectional imaging follow-up may also be helpful to ensure stability, potentially with pancreatic protocol CT correlation.
3.  Small left renal cyst.

Technique: Multiplanar, multisequence MRI of the cervical spine performed according to a standard protocol.

Findings:

Multilevel cervical spondylosis is most pronounced at C3-4, with disc desiccation, mild disc height loss, disc bulges and bilateral uncovertebral hypertrophy. Disc bulge is associated with slight compression of the ventral cord surface. No cord signal abnormality. Moderate canal stenosis and severe bilateral foraminal stenosies.

Additional milder disc bulges at C4-5 and C5-6 with lower-grade canal and foraminal narrowing. There is likely disc contact on the ventral cord at C4-5.

Impression:
Multilevel cervical spondylosis, most pronounced at C3-4 with mild cord compression, moderate canal stenosis, and several bilateral foraminal stenoses. No cord signal abnormality.

Technique: CT examination of the abdomen and pelvis was performed without intravenous contrast.

Findings:

There are several scattered, predominantly sub-centimeter low-attenuation lesions throughout the liver, most of which are too small to characterize. Largest in the hepatic dome measuring 1.4 cm.

There is a non-obstructing 6 mm stone in the lower pole of the right kidney. There is a 3 mm non-obstructing stone in the lower pole of the left kidney. No hydronephrosis. 
Impression: 
1. Multiple small low-attenuation liver lesions, many of which are too small to characterize but likely represent benign lesions such as cysts or hemangiomas. Recommend contrast enhanced CT or MRI of the abdomen for further characterization. 
2. Bilateral non-obstructing kidney stones. No hydronephrosis.

TECHNIQUE: Axial CT of the abdomen with intravenous contrast, multiplanar reformats performed.

FINDINGS:
Liver: Mild hepatic steatosis.  Mild hepatomegaly measures 19.0 cm in craniocaudal dimension. 

Pelvis: Bilateral adnexal cystic structures, measuring up to 5.1 cm on the left. 

IMPRESSION:
Mild hepatic steatosis.

Bilateral adnexal cystic structures measure up to 5.1 cm on the left, may represent ovarian cysts. Consider dedicated pelvic ultrasound for further evaluation.

Technique: 
CT of the Chest without contrast.

Findings: 
Mild cardiomegaly. Severe coronary artery calcifications and/or stents, although visualization is limited by motion artifact. Moderate bilateral lower lobe atelectasis. Trace pleural effusions.

Impression:
- Moderate bilateral lower lobe atelectasis. Pneumonia is less likely, though not excluded. 
- Trace pleural effusions.
- Mild cardiomegaly.

TECHNIQUE: 
Transaxial CT images of the chest were obtained with and without intravenous contrast.  Maximum intensity projection imaging was utilized for interpretation.

FINDINGS: 
Thoracic aorta atherosclerosis.  There is aneurysmal dilatation involving the ascending thoracic aorta measuring 4.8 x 4.7 cm.  The aortic arch measures 3.2 x 2.9 cm.  The descending thoracic aorta measures 3.1 x 3.0 cm. 

IMPRESSION:
Thoracic aorta atherosclerosis with aneurysm formation involving the ascending thoracic aorta.

Technique: 
CT of the Chest without contrast.

Findings: 
Moderate calcific atherosclerosis of the thoracic aorta. Ectasia of the ascending thoracic aorta, measuring 4.3 cm. 
3.8 x 2.6 cm smoothly marginated isoattenuating soft tissue mass in the anterior mediastinum.

Impression: 
1. Ectasia of the ascending thoracic aorta, measuring 4.3 cm.

2. Smoothly marginated isoattenuating soft tissue mass in the anterior mediastinum. The differential diagnosis includes a thymoma, thymic carcinoma, and lymphoma, among other etiologies. Further evaluation is recommended.

Technique:
CT abdomen and pelvis with contrast. Additional delay sequences of the abdomen were acquired. 

Findings:

Lung bases: Minimal atelectasis. Small pericardial effusion.  

Liver: Smooth contour. No mass. Portal vein is patent. 

Biliary: Gallbladder is nondistended. Choleliathisis. 

Pancreas: Unremarkable. 

Spleen: Unremarkable. 

Adrenals: Unremarkable. 

Kidneys: No hydronephrosis. No calculus. Right midpole renal cyst measures up to 2.3 cm. Retroaortic left renal vein. 

Bladder: Unremarkable. 

Bowel: Moderate colonic fecal retention. No bowel wall thickening. Normal appendix. Sigmoid diverticulosis. 

Aorta: Moderate atherosclerotic calcifications and soft plaque of the abdominal aorta. 

Bones: No aggressive osseous lesion. Minimal multilevel degenerative changes of the lumbar spine. 

Soft tissues: Unremarkable. 

Impression:
1. Cholelithiasis without evidence of acute cholecystitis. 
2. Simple right renal cyst. 
3. Sigmoid diverticulosis without evidence of diverticulitis.

Technique: Axial CT images acquired through the chest without contrast. Multiplanar reformats obtained. 

Findings:
Moderate to severe bronchiectasis in the left lower lobe.  Mild bronchiectasis and scarring in the right middle lobe.  No confluent pulmonary consolidation. 

Impression:
1.  Regional bronchiectasis in the left lower lobe and right middle lobe which is nonspecific, but would primarily consider chronic sequelae of old infection or inflammation.

TECHNIQUE: CT of the abdomen and pelvis with intravenous and oral contrast. Coronal and sagittal reconstructions were performed.

FINDINGS:
Lung Bases: Bilateral groundglass opacities. Cardiomegaly. Extensive coronary artery calcifications. The main pulmonary artery is dilated to 7.2 cm. Ascending aortic dilatation measures 7.2 cm. Nonspecific bilateral breast calcification. Right breast mass versus prominent tissue is partially imaged. Right chest wall catheter, partially imaged.

Liver: Normal in size. Patent hepatic and portal veins.

Gallbladder: Cholelithiasis without CT evidence of cholecystitis.

Spleen: Normal in size and contour.

Pancreas: Atrophic. No main pancreatic ductal dilatation.

Adrenals: Nonspecific right adrenal thickening. Normal left adrenal gland.

Kidneys: No hydronephrosis or obstructing calculi. Bilateral cysts and additional subcentimeter hypodensities, too small to characterize.

Bowel: Large hiatal hernia. No obstruction. Normal appendix. Colonic diverticulosis without evidence of diverticulitis.

Pelvic organs: Hysterectomy; unremarkable vaginal cuff. Distended urinary bladder.

Aorta: Extensive atherosclerotic calcification.

Bones: Multilevel degenerative changes of the spine, most prominent at L5-S1 where there is likely high grade spinal canal and neural-foraminal compression. Severe bilateral hip osteoarthrosis. Diffuse osteopenia. 


IMPRESSION:

Large hiatal hernia with bilateral pulmonary ground glass opacities. Correlate for aspiration risk and consider dedicated lung CT for further evaluation.

Right breast mass versus prominent tissue is incompletely characterized. Correlate with prior imaging if available or obtain dedicated breast imaging.

Cardiomegaly. Ascending aortic aneurysm measures 7.2 cm. 

Dilatation of the main pulmonary artery can be seen in the setting of pulmonary hypertension.

Cholelithiasis without CT evidence for cholecystitis.

Multilvel degenerative changes of the spine, most prominent at L5-S1 where there is likely high grade spinal canal and neural-foraminal compression.

Small hiatal hernia containing oral contrast material which may indicate gastroesophageal reflux disease. 

Diffuse low attenuation of the liver likely reflects a diffusely fatty liver, decreasing the sensitivity to detect a liver lesion.

Surgical clips in the right upper abdominal quadrant reflect sequela of prior cholecystectomy. 

Punctate calcified nonobstructing calyceal stones in both kidneys.

Small fat containing left inguinal hernia.

Diffuse bony demineralization.

Sub-centimeter sclerotic lesion in the left anterolateral 6th rib likely reflects a bone island in the absence of known malignancy.

Degenerative changes of the visualized spine. Schmorl's nodes in the visualized thoracolumbar spine at T11/T12 and L2/L3. Disc degenerative disease of the visualized spine.

Technique: Axial CT images acquired through the abdomen. IV contrast administered with portal venous and delayed phase imaging acquired.  Sagittal and coronal MPR image postprocessing performed. 

Findings:
The lung bases are clear.

The liver is mildly enlarged measuring up to 19 cm in craniocaudad length.  Small area of geographic hypoattenuation in the left hepatic lobe which persists on delayed phase imaging.  Normal hepatic vasculature traverses the area of hypoattenuation.  

Normal gallbladder, pancreas, and spleen. 

Normal adrenal glands and bilateral kidneys. 

Normal appearance of the stomach, partially imaged small bowel, and partially imaged colon.  No intestinal obstruction or free air.  The partially visualized appendix is normal.

Abdominal aorta is normal in caliber at 1.6 cm diameter.  No AAA.  

Old, healed fractures of left ribs 8 and 9. No lytic or blastic osseous lesions.  

IMPRESSION:
1.  Mild hepatomegaly containing a small geographic area of hypoattenuation in the left hepatic lobe consistent with focal fatty infiltration.

2.  Old healed fractures of left-sided ribs 8 and 9.

TECHNIQUE:
MRI of the brain without contrast.

FINDINGS:
No acute territorial infarct or hemorrhage on the available images. There is mild global cerebral atrophy, most marked in the frontotemporal region. No hydrocephalus. Periventricular and subcortical T2 hyperintensities are compatible with chronic microvascular ischemic changes.  Paranasal sinuses are clear.

IMPRESSION:
Mild cerebral atrophy and chronic microvascular ischemic changes. No acute intracranial findings.

TECHNIQUE:  Multi-planar, multi-sequence MRI of the lumbar spine without contrast. 


FINDINGS:

Mild anterolisthesis of L5 on S1 is present.  Mild degenerative intervertebral disc space narrowing at L5 - S1 is noted.  Increased T1 and increased T2 signal at the inferior endplate of L5 and the superior endplate of S1 are consistent with Modic Type II changes at the L5 - S1 interspace.     


DISCUSSION:

1.  Mild anterolisthesis of L5 on S1 with degenerative intervertebral disc space narrowing and Modic Type II endplate changes at the L5 - S1 interspace.  

Modic Type II endplate changes occur when active red marrow is replaced with fat as a function of degenerative marrow ischemia.  (www.radiopaedia.org)

TECHNIQUE: Multiple transaxial images of the abdomen obtained after IV and oral contrast administration. 


FINDINGS: 
The liver demonstrates patchy heterogeneous enhancement, surface nodularity consistent with cirrhosis.  

There is recanalization of the umbilical vein and splenomegaly, findings that indicate portal hypertension.  

IMPRESSION:

Evidence of cirrhosis with stigmata of portal hypertension including splenomegaly and recanalization of the umbilical vein.

Technique: Multiplanar multisequential imaging of the abdomen was performed with and without IV contrast
 
Findings:
Liver: Shrunken and nodular contour compatible with cirrhosis. No suspicious liver masses.
Gallbladder: Non distended gallbladder containing cholelithiasis. No gallbladder wall thickening or pericholecystic fluid.

Impression:
1. Cirrhotic liver, no suspicious liver masses.
2. Cholelithiasis without evidence of acute cholecystitis.

CLINICAL INDICATION: Disc herniation      

TECHNIQUE: 
Multiplanar multisequence MRI of the cervical spine was obtained with and without intravenous contrast.

FINDINGS:

Localizer: No visualized findings.

Alignment: 2 mm retrolisthesis of C2 on C3.

Ligaments: Intact.

Bone marrow: Mild endplate edema at C5-C6 and C6-C7.

Vertebrae: C3-C6 posterior spinal laminectomy and fusion. Multilevel degenerative changes as follows:  

C6-C7:  Small disc osteophyte complex, mild bilateral facet arthropathy, uncovertebral hypertrophy, resulting in mild spinal canal stenosis, mild left and mild right neural foraminal narrowing.

Cord: Increased cord signal spanning C2-C3. Additional possible cord thinning at T3-T4. No cord enhancement.

Visualized prevertebral and paraspinal soft tissues: Within normal limits.

Visualized brain: No acute findings.

IMPRESSION:
Multilevel degenerative changes of the cervical spine as above, most prominent at C6-C7 where there is mild spinal canal stenosis and mild bilateral neural foraminal narrowing.
Increased cord signal spanning C2-C3, which may represent myelomalacia. No cord enhancement.
Additional possible cord thinning at T3-T4, incompletely evaluated. Consider dedicated thoracic spine MRI for further evaluation.

TECHNIQUE:
Multidetector CT images of the abdomen and pelvis were obtained before and after the administration of contrast.  Multiplanar reformats.  Delayed series of images also obtained.

FINDINGS:
Mild to moderate cardiac enlargement.  Right renal lesion containing macroscopic fat at the posterior interpolar region measuring 3.4 cm. Peripherally calcified 8.6 cm lesion of the lateral interpolar region of the right kidney with some central hyperdensity with precontrast attenuation of 23 and postcontrast attenuation of 29.

Cholelithiasis.

IMPRESSION:
1. Hemorrhagic/proteinaceous cyst of the right kidney.
2. Right renal angiomyolipoma.
3. Benign cysts of the liver.  Hyperenhancing lesions most consistent with flash fill hemagiomas or perfustional anomalies.
4. Cholelithiasis.

TECHNIQUE:  Multiplanar, multi-sequence MRI of the cervical spine without contrast. 


FINDINGS:

The cervical spine is well aligned.  No abnormal signal is noted in the cervical cord.  Small disc protrusions are noted at the C4 - C5, C5 - C6 and C6 - C7 interspaces.  No significant stenosis of the spinal canal or neuroforamina is appreciated at any level.

Indication: None 

Technique: CT chest was obtained from the jugular notch through the posterior costophrenic recess without IV contrast. Coronal and sagittal reformats as well as higher kernel algorithm reconstruction was performed.


FINDINGS:

Lungs/Pleura: Severe centrilobular emphysema with upper lobe predominance and diffuse bronchial wall thickening, consistent with smoking-related lung disease. There is a 2.4 cm irregular soft tissue thickening with internal scattered calcification in the right upper lobe apex in proximity to adjacent pleural thickening. To a lesser degree, there is irregular soft tissue thickening in the left upper lobe apex measuring up to 3 mm. Dominant right upper lobe apex bullae measuring up to 5 cm and 4.6 cm

Right basilar juxta pleural scarring identified in the lateral basal right lobe. 


IMPRESSION

 1) Severe centrilobular emphysema with upper lobe predominance, associated diffuse bronchial wall thickening, and large right apical bullae measuring up to 5.0 cm, consistent with smoking-related lung disease.

 2) Irregular 2.4 cm soft tissue thickening in the right upper lobe apex with internal scattered calcifications and adjacent pleural thickening. Mild irregular apical thickening in the left upper lobe. Findings are indeterminate, with differential considerations including post-inflammatory or post-granulomatous scarring versus neoplasm. Correlation with prior imaging is recommended. In the absence of prior studies, consider further evaluation with PET/CT or short-interval follow-up CT based on clinical risk factors.

Indication: None

Technique: Multiplanar CT of the thoracic spine was performed followed the intrathecal administration of iodinated contrast.

Findings:

Vertebral body heights are preserved. 

There is a small right central disc protrusion at T6-7, which slightly indents the right ventral cord. 

The remaining thoracic disc spaces are maintained. 

Impression: Small right central disc protrusion at T6-T7 which slightly indents the right ventral cord.

Technique: CT of the Chest without contrast.

Findings: Mild paraseptal emphysema. Mild scattered linear atelectasis or scars throughout the lungs. Scattered subcentimeter calcified granulomata in the right lung. No pulmonary nodule, mass, or focal consolidation. Normal heart size. No significant pericardial effusion. Moderate coronary artery calcifications. Moderate calcific atherosclerosis of the thoracic aorta. Ascending thoracic aorta aneurysm, measuring 4.8 cm. Bilateral breast implants.

Impression:
- Mild paraseptal emphysema.
- 4.8 cm ascending thoracic aorta aneurysm.
- Moderate calcific atherosclerosis of the thoracic aorta. 
- Moderate coronary artery calcifications.

Technique: CT of the Chest without contrast.

Findings: 0.2 cm left upper lobe calcified granuloma. 0.2 cm perifissural calcified granuloma in the left lower lobe. Mild left lower lobe atelectasis. No significant pulmonary emphysema or bronchiectasis. Mild calcific atherosclerosis of the thoracic aorta. 

Impression:
- No significant pulmonary emphysema or bronchiectasis. 
- Evidence of old, healed granulomatous disease.

Technique:  Multiplanar multi-echo imaging of the pelvis.  Pre and post contrast images acquired.  

Findings:    

Prior hysterectomy.  No abscess.  Normal appearance of the left and right ovaries.  

Impression: 

Prior hysterectomy.  No abscess.

Technique: Routine MR of the brain was obtained, including axial DWI, axial T1 weighted pre and post contrast sequences, post contrast 3D CUBE with coronal and sagittal reformats, axial and sagittal T2, axial FLAIR with fat saturation, axial gradient echo, 

Findings:
No restricted diffusion.
No acute intracranial hemorrhage. No abnormal susceptibility artifact.
Small blush of ill defined parenchymal enhancement in the right posterior temporal lobe. 
Encephalomalacia and gliosis in the medial left parietal and occipital lobes. 
The skull base flow voids are present. 
Ex vacuo dilation of the atrium and occipital horn of the left lateral ventricle. No acute hydrocephalus.

The visualized orbits are unremarkable. The calvarium is normal. The visualized paranasal sinuses are well clear. 

Impression:
No acute intracranial abnormality.
Chronic medial left parieto-occipital infarct.
Small blush of parenchymal enhancement in the right temporal lobe, likely reflect a benign vascular lesion such as developmental venous anomaly.

Technique: CT of the Chest, Abdomen, and Pelvis pre- and post-IV contrast administration.

Findings: Mild linear atelectasis in the lower lobes. No pulmonary nodule, mass, focal consolidation, or bronchiectasis. Partially visualized left subclavian vein catheter terminating near the atriocaval junction. Normal heart size. No pericardial effusion. Cholecystectomy clips. Normal liver, pancreas, and spleen. Normal kidneys. Sutures from prior sigmoidectomy; anastomosis intact. No bowel obstruction. Moderate thoracic degenerative disc disease. 2.5 cm hemangioma in the L2 vertebral body.  Sacral dural ectasia.  Subcentimeter sclerotic lesions in the right iliac bone, right acetabulum, and right femoral head.

Impression: 
- No acute abnormality.
- 2.5 cm benign hemangioma in the L2 vertebral body.
- Subcentimeter sclerotic lesions, as described, are most consistent with benign bone islands. A nuclear medicine bone scan may provide additional characterization if there is concern for malignancy.

TECHNIQUE: Multidetector CT images of the abdomen and pelvis were obtained without intravenous contrast. Multiplanar reformats submitted.

FINDINGS:
Liver: No suspicious focal lesions. Mild nodular hepatic contour.

Spleen: No splenomegaly.

No ascites. 

IMPRESSION:
Mild nodular hepatic contour, which may be seen in the setting of early cirrhosis. No CT evidence of portal hypertension.

Technique: Non-contrast CT of the chest.

Findings: Bilateral lower lobe pulmonary groundglass opacities with very mild bronchiectasis, likely represents scarring and/or pulmonary fibrosis. No honeycombing.  No pleural effusion.

IMPRESSION: 
Mild basilar predominant pulmonary fibrosis.

Technique: Contrast-enhanced CT of the abdomen and pelvis was performed. Multiplanar reformats were obtained and reviewed.

Findings:
Borderline central intrahepatic and mild extrahepatic biliary dilatation without a radiodense filling defect is presumably due to the postcholecystectomy reservoir state.

Mild bilateral renal cortical thinning without a suspicious renal mass or hydronephrosis. Unremarkable urinary bladder. Prior hysterectomy.  Ovaries not visualized.

There is a small sliding type hernia marked by slight superior migration of the gastric fundus above the diaphragmic hiatus. A focal outpouching is identified arising from the gastric fundus, which is compatible with a moderate sized gastric fundal diverticulum. Appendectomy surgical clips. Multiple small focal outpouchings are present in the sigmoid colon, which are compatible with colonic diverticulosis. There are no adjacent inflammatory changes. 

There is minimal central mesenteric haziness without an associated mass, calcifications, or retractions of the bowel. This is suggestive of mesenteric panniculitis. Multifocal atherosclerotic changes, which are most prominent in the distal descending thoracic aorta. 

Impression:
1. Small hiatal hernia. 
3. Moderate sized gastric fundal diverticulum. 
4. Colonic diverticulosis.
5. Mild mesenteric panniculitis.

TECHNIQUE: MRI of the brain utilizing sagittal 3D T1 MPRAGE, axial T2-weighted, axial diffusion-weighted with ADC map, axial T1-weighted, axial susceptibility-weighted, and axial T2 FLAIR sequences.

FINDINGS:

There is no evidence of recent infarction on the diffusion-weighted sequence. There is moderate volume loss. Moderate hyperintense signal is seen in the cerebral white matter bilaterally on the FLAIR and T2-weighted sequences with mild pontine involvement, likely chronic ischemic. No abnormal magnetic susceptibility effect is noted to indicate previous hemorrhage. There is no hydrocephalus or midline shift. Ventricular enlargement appears proportionate to the degree of surrounding atrophy. The central intracranial arterial flow voids are grossly maintained.

Mild mucosal thickening is seen in the left sphenoid sinus. There is nasal septal deviation to the right. The mastoid air cells are clear. The patient has had bilateral intraocular lens replacement.


IMPRESSION:
No acute infarct. Moderate diffuse cerebral parenchymal atrophy. White matter changes most likely related to chronic ischemia.

Technique: CT of the Chest without contrast.

Findings: Moderate centrilobular emphysema with an upper lobe predominance. Associated right apical parenchymal scars. Diffuse mild bronchial wall thickening and cylindrical bronchiectasis, most prominent in the lower lobes. 

Impression:
- Moderate centrilobular emphysema with an upper lobe predominance. 
- Diffuse mild bronchial wall thickening and cylindrical bronchiectasis.

Technique: CT of the Chest, Abdomen, and Pelvis following oral contrast administration.

Findings: Normal heart size. 4.8 cm fusiform aneurysm of the ascending thoracic aorta. Prior coronary artery bypass graft and median sternotomy. 1.3 cm calcified right renal artery aneurysm. Prostatomegaly, measuring 7.4 x 5.5 x 3.8 cm. Moderate thoracolumbar degenerative disc disease.

Impression: 
- 4.8 cm fusiform aneurysm of the ascending thoracic aorta.
- Prior median sternotomy and coronary artery bypass graft.
- 1.3 cm calcified right renal artery aneurysm.
- Prostatomegaly.
