custom_fields->>'field_4e36a47c160a4a468:
EXAM:  MRI Abdomen and MRCP without contrast

FINDINGS:
Patient is status post cholecystectomy.  There is a small dilated cystic duct remnant.  The common bile duct is normal in caliber.  The pancreatic duct is normal in caliber.  There is no evidence for pancreatic divisum.  The pancreas appears normal.  

Multiple, at least 8, small simple cysts are seen scattered throughout the liver, many of which show probable connections to intrahepatic bile ducts on the MRCP.  The largest of these is seen just anterior to the porta hepatis within hepatic segment IV, measuring 11 x 13 mm in axial plane. 

Bowel loops are normal in caliber.  The spleen and adrenal glands are normal.  No free fluid is seen.  There is mild pelviectasis of the right renal collecting system without frank hydronephrosis.  No renal cysts are seen.  The left kidney is normal.

A small T2 hyperintense round bone lesion at the superior endplate of L3 is likely a benign vertebral body hemangioma.  There is moderate degenerative disc disease at L4-L5 and L5-S1.
 
IMPRESSION:
1.  Post-cholecystectomy changes with a small cystic duct remnant.  No evidence for choledocholithiasis or biliary duct dilation.
2.  Multiple small simple appearing cysts in the liver, some of which show probable connections to intrahepatic bile ducts.  These are most likely biliary hamartomas.
3.  Moderate degenerative disc changes of the lower lumbar spine.

Technique: 
Sagittal and axial MRI images of the lumbar spine without IV contrast

Findings:
The conus medullaris is at the level of T12-L1.  The visualized vertebral body heights are within normal limits.  The lumbar spine alignment is within normal limits.  There are sacral Tarlov cysts which are more prominent on the right side at the level of S1-2. Multilevel disc bulges in the lower lumbar spine. These are most marked at L5-S1, where there is a disc bulge with associated inferiorly oriented right paracentral herniated component. There is associated mild spinal canal narrowing.  There is bilateral facet hypertrophy with mild to moderate bilateral neuroforaminal narrowing.

Impression:
L5-S1 disc bulge/herniation and facet hypertrophy resulting in spinal canal and neuroforaminal narrowing.

Technique:  
Sagittal and axial images of the lumbar spine without IV contrast as well as scout coronal images of the lumbar spine. 

Findings:
The conus medullaris is at the level of L1.  The visualized vertebral body heights are within normal limits. Vertebral body hemangiomas are seen at T11, L3, and L4.  There is slight leftward curvature of the lower lumbar spine. Multi-level disc protrusions, most marked at L5-S1, where there is a disc bulge with an associated right paracentral herniated component, resulting in moderate spinal canal narrowing.  There is bilateral facet hypertrophy with mild to moderate bilateral neuroforaminal narrowing.

Impression:
L5-S1 disc bulge/herniation and facet hypertrophy resulting in spinal canal and neuroforaminal narrowing.

Technique:
CT of the Abdomen, and Pelvis with contrast.

Findings: L
10.8 x 5.5 cm hypoattenuating, hypoenhancing central hepatic mass with mild peripheral enhancement. No intrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation. Patent portal vein. Mild ascites. Moderate degenerative disc disease.

Impression: 
- 10.8 x 5.5 cm hypoattenuating, hypoenhancing central hepatic mass with mild peripheral enhancement, concerning for hepatic malignancy or cholangiocarcinoma.
- Mild ascites.

Technique: 
CTA of the Chest.

Findings: 
Normal heart size. Trace pericardial effusion. Ascending thoracic aorta aneurysm, measuring 5.2 cm. 

Impression: 
- 5.2 cm ascending thoracic aorta aneurysm.
- Trace pericardial effusion.

Technique: 
Axial CT images of the brain were acquired with both 3.0 and 0.6 mm slices. Coronal and sagittal reformats were also obtained. 

Findings:

No acute intracranial hemorrhage or acute transcortical territorial infarction. No midline shift or mass effect.

Multiple chronic infarcts in the bilateral frontal lobes and right parietal lobe. 

Small chronic infarcts in both cerebellar hemispheres. 

Additional areas of hypoattenuation in the supratentorial white matter are non specific but likely reflect chronic microvascular ischemic changes. Intracranial atherosclerosis.

Cerebral atrophy with proportional ventricular enlargement. Asymmetric ex vacuo dilation of the right lateral ventricle. No acute hydrocephalus.

No aggressive osseous lesions. 

The visualized orbits are unremarkable. The visualized paranasal sinuses are clear. The mastoid air cells are well aerated. 

Impression:
No acute intracranial abnormality. 

Multiple chronic infarcts involving the bilateral frontal lobes, right parietal lobe and bilateral cerebellar hemispheres.

Technique: CT of the Abdomen and Pelvis without contrast.

Findings: Mild linear atelectasis or scars in the visualized lung bases. Cholelithiasis. 3 mm nonobstructing calculus in the upper pole of the left kidney. Calcified uterine fibroids. Severe calcific atherosclerosis of the abdominal aorta and visualized femoral arterial system. Large hiatal hernia, partially visualized. Diffuse, mild pericolonic inflammatory fat stranding and questionable mural thickening. Moderate degenerative disc disease of the visualized thoracolumbar spine. L4-L5 fusion hardware.

Impression: 
- Large hiatal hernia, partially visualized.
- Cholelithiasis.
- Calcified uterine fibroids.
- Findings suggestive of diffuse, mild colitis. No obstruction.

Technique: 
CT images of the abdomen and pelvis were obtained after the administration of intravenous contrast.  Multiplanar reformatted images were provided

Findings: 
Vasculature: The infrarenal abdominal aorta is aneurysmal measuring up to 3.9 cm on axial images. There is a short segment dissection of the distal abdominal aorta, likely chronic. There is a partially thrombosed saccular aneurysm of the left internal iliac artery measuring up to 1.5 x 1.2 cm.

Impression:
Infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm measuring up to 3.9 cm.  

Left internal iliac artery aneurysm measuring up to 1.5 cm.

Technique: Multiplanar multisequence MRI of the lumbar spine was performed without contrast. 

Findings:
Transitional lumbosacral anatomy with a lumbarized S1 segment and an S1-S2 disc. 

At S1-S2 there is loss of disc height and T2 signal with a large left subarticular extrusion which effaces the left lateral recess and likely impinges on the left S2 nerve root. Mild central canal stenosis. Mild facet hypertrophy. No foraminal stenosis. 

Multilevel degenerative changes noted elsewhere in the lumbar spine. Paraspinal soft tissues unremarkable. Normal conus. 

Impression:
1. At S1-S2 there is a large large left subarticular extrusion which effaces the left lateral recess and likely impinges on the left S2 nerve root. Mild associated central canal stenosis.
2. Multilevel degenerative changes elsewhere.

TECHNIQUE: Multidetector CT images of the chest were obtained with intravenous contrast. Multiplanar reformats submitted.

FINDINGS:
Upper Abdomen: Small volume ascites with diffuse peritoneal thickening. 

IMPRESSION:
Small volume ascites with peritoneal thickening, raising concern for neoplasm. Additional workup with CT abdomen/pelvis with intravenous contrast is recommended.

Technique: Axial, coronal and sagittal CT of the abdomen and pelvis with intravenous and oral contrast material.

Findings:
Sub-5 mm solid nodule along the right oblique fissure.

Surgical clips in the right upper abdominal quadrant reflect sequela of prior cholecystectomy. 

Tiny fat containing umbilical hernia.

Postsurgical changes in the anterior abdominal wall.

5.1 x 3.6 x 4.8 cm (AP x TRV x CC) heterogeneous mass in the myometrium of the right uterine body causing mass effect on the endometrial canal which is displaced anteriorly and to the left and demonstrates an abnormal contour.
Heterogeneity and contour abnormality of the uterus.

Mildly fluid filled endometrial and endocervical canal.

3.4 cm water attenuating left ovarian structure.

Mild posterior disc bulge at L4/L5 and L5/S1.


Impression:
5.1 x 3.6 x 4.8 cm (AP x TRV x CC) heterogeneous mass in the myometrium of the right uterine body causing mass effect on the endometrial canal which is displaced anteriorly and to the left and demonstrates an abnormal contour, likely reflecting an intramural uterine leiomyoma with a submucosal component. Heterogeneity and contour abnormality of the uterus suggests additional uterine leiomyomata. Pelvic ultrasound is recommended for further evaluation and characterization.

3.4 cm water attenuating left ovarian structure likely reflects an ovarian cyst.

Sub-5 mm solid nodule along the right oblique fissure could reflect a perifissural lymph node or solid pulmonary nodule. Comparison with prior studies is recommended to assess stability. If no prior studies are available or this finding is new, further management is recommended per guidelines of MacMahon H., et al. Guidelines for Management of Incidental Pulmonary Nodules Detected on CT Images: From the Fleischner Society 2017 unless the patient is aged 35 years or younger or the patient has a history of malignancy or immunosuppression in which case further management should be based on clinical grounds.

Other findings noted above.

Technique: Axial, coronal and sagittal CT of the abdomen and pelvis with intravenous and oral contrast material.

Findings:
Small to moderate hiatal hernia.
Several scattered colonic diverticula.

Low attenuation in the region of the falciform ligament likely reflects focal fat.

9.1 x 9.7 x 15.6 cm (AP x TRV x CC) enlarged, multilobulated uterus containing subserosal, pedunculated masses at the uterine fundus and heterogeneously enhancing intramural masses in the uterine fundus and body. For example, an 8.2 x 6.8 cm heterogeneously enhancing mass at the posterior uterine body. These intramural masses cause mass effect on the endometrial canal which is effaced and distorted.

The enlarged, multilobulated uterus causes mass effect on the bilateral distal ureters causing bilateral mild hydroureteronephrosis.

Tampon within the vagina.

2.3 cm water attenuating right ovarian structure likely reflects an ovarian follicle.

Small fat containing umbilical hernia.

Indeterminate 1.3 cm water attenuating structure in the subcutaneous soft tissues of the anterior abdominal wall located inferior to the umbilicus.

Grade 1 retrolisthesis of L4 on L5 and L5 on S1.

Mild posterior disc bulge at L4/L5 and L5/S1.

Impression:
Enlarged, multilobulated uterus containing subserosal, pedunculated, and intramural masses, likely reflecting uterine leiomyomata. The intramural masses efface and distort the endometrial canal, indicating submucosal components of uterine leiomyomata. Consider pelvic ultrasound or pelvic MRI for further characterization/to help determine subsequent management strategy.

The enlarged, multilobulated uterus causes mass effect on the distal ureters causing bilateral mild hydroureteronephrosis.

TECHNIQUE: CT of the abdomen and pelvis with IV contrast with multiplaner reformats. Additional delayed axial images obtained. 

FINDINGS:
Multiple circumscribed, homogenous, thin-walled bilateral renal cysts measuring 5 HU on both the venous and delayed phases. There are three cysts on the left, largest in the interpolar region measuring 4.3 x 3.9 x 3.5 cm. There are three cysts on the right, largest in the interpolar region measuring 2.0 x 2.2 x 2.5 cm. No associated enhancement, calcification, septation, or soft tissue component. 

IMPRESSION:
1. Benign simple bilateral renal cysts (Bosniak I) requiring no follow up.

Technique: Routine unenhanced MR of the thoracic spine was performed, including axial and sagittal T1 weighted, axial and sagittal T2-weighted and sagittal STIR.

Findings:

There is a  round, well circumscribed lesion in the T5 vertebral body which hyperintense signal abnormality on T1, T2 and STIR. The lesion demonstrates a salt and pepper appearance on axial T2 weighted sequence.

Multilevel disc dessication.

Vertebral body heights are preserved. 

Impression: 

Round, well circumscribed lesion at T5 consistent with benign lipid poor venous malformation/hemangioma.

TECHNIQUE: 
Head CT was performed utilizing contiguous axial CT sections from the skull base to the vertex without the use of IV contrast. 

FINDINGS: 
There is no hydrocephalus, mass, mass effect, extra-axial fluid collection or acute intracranial hemorrhage.  There is no recent transcortical infarct or remote infarct. 
There is mild polypoid mucosal thickening in the left frontal sinus. 
There is enlargement of the posterior nasopharyngeal soft tissues, likely reactive in nature. 

IMPRESSION: 
Normal noncontrast head CT.

Technique:  
Sagittal, coronal, and axial MRI sequences of the lumbar spine without IV contrast.

Findings: 
The conus medullaris is at the level of L1-2.  The visualized vertebral body heights are within normal limits.  There is a small left renal cyst.  The alignment of the lumbar spine is within normal limits. There are post surgical changes of the subcutaneous fat posterior to the L5 spinous process.  There is abnormal signal at the L5 spinous process consistent with partial laminectomy at the level of L5-S1. Mild disc bulges throughout the lower lumbar spine, including at L5-S1 where there is a disc bulge resulting in mild spinal canal narrowing. At this level, there is also  bilateral facet hypertrophy resulting in moderate bilateral neuroforaminal narrowing.

Impression:
Multilevel lumbar disc bulges and facet hypertrophy resulting in spinal canal and neuroforaminal narrowing.

Technique: 
Multiphase CT images of the abdomen in non-contrast, arterial and venous phase. 

Findings:
Liver is normal in size and contour. There are bilateral masses demonstrating peripheral nodular enhancement, the largest being in segment 7 and measuring 2.9 cm.

Impression: 
Multiple, discontinuous peripherally enhancing masses in the liver, most compatible with hemangiomas.

TECHNIQUE: 
Noncontrast chest CT was performed.  Coronal and sagittal reformatted images were created. 


FINDINGS: 
There is mild centrilobular emphysema with an upper lobe predilection.  There is mild hyperinflation in keeping with air trapping. 

There is a small amount of fluid within the pericardial sac, notably anteriorly, favored to be physiologic in nature.  There is no hemopericardium or cardiomegaly. 


IMPRESSION: 
Mild centrilobular emphysema with an upper lobe predilection and associated air trapping. 

Small amount of pericardial fluid, favored to be physiologic in nature.
abf

Technique:
Multiplanar CT of the chest, abdomen and pelvis with oral contrast material.

Findings:
2.5 x 1.9 cm water attenuating lesion in the anterior interpolar right kidney likely reflects cyst. Status post left nephrectomy with surgical clips in the surgical bed.

Impression:
Right renal cyst. Status post left nephrectomy.

Technique: CT of the Chest, Abdomen, and Pelvis with oral contrast and without IV contrast.

Findings: Calcified mediastinal and right hilar lymph nodes. Scattered subcentimeter hepatic and splenic calcifications. The caudate lobe of the liver is enlarged. No discrete mass identified. Questionable mild contour nodularity of the liver.

Impression:
- Enlarged caudate lobe of the liver. No discrete mass identified on these unenhanced views. Questionable mild hepatic contour nodularity. The differential diagnosis includes: cirrhosis, Budd-Chiari syndrome, and covert neoplasm, among other etiologies. Further evaluation is recommended with a contrast-enhanced MRI of the liver.
- Evidence of old, healed granulomatous disease.

Technique: CT of the Abdomen and Pelvis pre- and post-IV contrast administration.

Findings: 3.8 x 3.7 cm soft tissue mass with coarse calcifications in the posterior mid pole of the left kidney is iso-attenuating on the pre-contrast images, slightly heterogeneous on post-contrast images, and iso-attenuating on delayed images. 2.1 cm exophytic smoothly marginated simple cyst arising from the mid pole of the right kidney, demonstrating no significant contrast enhancement. Shotty retroperitoneal and bilateral inguinal lymph nodes.

Impression: 
- 3.8 x 3.7 cm soft tissue mass with coarse calcifications in the posterior mid pole of the left kidney, concerning for malignancy. 
- Shotty retroperitoneal and bilateral inguinal lymph nodes, benign versus malignant.

TECHNIQUE:   Noncontrast CT abdomen and pelvis.  Multiplanar reformats submitted.

FINDINGS:
The lung bases are clear.

Simple appearing 2.3 cm left renal cyst.  Small 2 mm calcification with the left renal cortex may represent small nonobstructive intrarenal calculus versus cortical calcification.  Small 3 mm nonobstructive calculus in the inferior pole of the left kidney.  No evidence of ureteral calculi, bladder calculi, or hydronephrosis.

Heavy aortoiliac atherosclerosis. Multiple pelvic surgical clips.   

Pancreatic atrophy.  Indeterminate 9 mm left adrenal nodule. 

Status post cholecystectomy with likely associated pneumobilia. 
Anterior abdominal wall post surgical changes with multiple incisional hernias, the largest of which contains loops of unobstructed small bowel.  No evidence of associated strangulation.

The uterus is surgically absent.   

Irregular soft tissue thickening of the anorectal region, measuring up to approximately 3 cm in thickness for which acute inflammatory process or infiltrative malignancy is not ruled out. Recommend correlation with clinical history and physical exam.

Degenerative changes of the lumbar spine and bilateral hips. 

IMPRESSION:
- Small left renal calcifications measuring up to 3 mm, likely representing nonobstructive intrarenal calculi.  No evidence of ureteral calculi or hydronephrosis.

- Irregular soft tissue thickening of the anorectal region, measuring up to approximately 3 cm in thickness which may represent acute inflammatory process or hemorrhoids however infiltrative malignancy is not ruled out.  Recommend correlation with clinical history and physical exam.

- Simple appearing left renal cyst.

- Heavy aortoiliac atherosclerosis.

- Anterior abdominal wall post surgical changes with several uncomplicated hernias, as above.

- Status post cholecystectomy with pneumobilia.

- Pancreatic atrophy.

- Indeterminate 9 mm left adrenal nodule.  Given subcentimeter size, no further follow up is indicated.

TECHNIQUE: 
Multiplanar, multisequence noncontrast thoracic spine MRI was performed. 


FINDINGS: 
There is an acute, mild, benign T1 superior endplate compression fracture with osseous edema but no retropulsion or canal compromise. 

There is an acute, mild, benign T2 superior endplate compression fracture with osseous edema but no retropulsion or canal compromise. 

There is an acute, mild, benign T3 superior endplate compression fracture with osseous edema but no retropulsion or canal compromise. 

There is an acute, mild, benign T4 superior endplate compression fracture with osseous edema but no retropulsion or canal compromise. 

There is an acute, moderate benign T5 superior endplate compression fracture with osseous edema.  There is retropulsion of the posterior/superior fracture fragment mildly the flattening the ventral thoracic cord without edema or gliosis. 


IMPRESSION: 
Acute moderate, benign T5 superior endplate compression fracture with osseous edema, retropulsion and mild impingement of the ventral thoracic cord. 

Acute mild, benign T1-4 superior endplate compression fractures with osseous edema but no retropulsion or canal compromise at these levels.

Technique: 
CT of the Chest without contrast.

Findings: 
Mild biapical scars. Diffuse, mild, mosaic ground glass opacities throughout the lungs, with a slight upper lobe predominance. Partially visualized lower cervical fusion hardware. Mild thoracic degenerative disc disease.

Impression:
Diffuse, mild, mosaic ground glass opacities throughout the lungs, with a slight upper lobe predominance. Though nonspecific, the differential diagnosis includes: mild viral or pneumocystis pneumonia, hypersensitivity pneumonitis, sarcoidosis, nonspecific interstitial pneumonia, and pulmonary edema.

TECHNIQUE: Multiplanar multisequence MRI of the lumbar spine without intravenous contrast.

FINDINGS:

There is moderate chronic anterior wedge compression of T12. No associated osseous edema is present. There is trace bony retropulsion. There is no subluxation. Artifact is present from bilateral screws and rods at T11 and L1.


IMPRESSION:

Chronic T12 compression fracture with metallic stabilization.

Technique: Multiplanar MRI without intravenous contrast

Findings:
Multilevel compression deformities of the lower thoracic and lumbar spine. There are chronic fractures with mild (~ 20%) height loss of L4, L3, and T11 vertebral bodies, as indicated by lack of T2 signal intensity within the vertebral body. There is approximately 90% vertebral body height loss of T12 vertebral body with linear T2/STIR hyperintense signal corresponding to a linear T1 hypointense signal, indicative of an acute vertebral compression fracture. There is approximately 3 mm retropulsion at the superior aspect without posterior cortex bulging. This creates mild spinal canal stenosis at this level without contact to the cord or any cord signal abnormality. Additionally, there is mild left neuroforaminal stenosis at the T11/T12 level. There is an exaggerated kyphosis at this level.

Multilevel disc disease without associated high grade spinal canal or neuroforaminal stenosis.

Impression:
Severe acute T12 compression fracture, likely osteoporotic, with associated spinal canal and neuroforaminal stenosis.

Other chronic compression fractures and multilevel degenerative changes.

Technique:
Multiplanar, multisequence MRI of the abdomen with and without contrast. 
Evaluation is limited due to motion artifact on multiple sequences

Findings:
There are 3 lesions in segment 7 of the liver that demonstrate T2 hyperintensity with peripheral nodular discontinuous enhancement with centripetal filling on more delayed phases of imaging. There is no arterial hyperenhancement or washout. There is T2 shine through with increased signal on both DWI and ADC sequences but no diffusion restriction. These findings are compatible with hemangiomas. The largest adjacent to the intrahepatic IVC and right hepatic vein measures 2.3 x 1.9 cm.

There is a left midpole T2 hyperintense nonenhancing lesion with a thin wall measuring up to 1.7 cm. No septations or nodular enhancing component is identified. No diffusion restriction. 

Impression
Hemangiomas in segment 7 of the liver with the dominant lesion measuring up to 2.3 cm.
Bosniak 1 1.7 cm left midpole renal cyst.

TECHNIQUE: MRI of the thoracic spine obtained with sagittal T2, STIR, T1 images. Axial T1 and T2 images obtained.


FINDINGS:  
Mild to moderate edema at the superior endplate of T11 with central 20% height loss and no retropulsion. There is linear low signal paralleling the superior endplate consistent with a fracture. No epidural hematoma. No evidence of tear of the anterior and posterior longitudinal ligaments or ligamentum flavum. No edema at the interspinous ligaments or paraspinal muscles.

Chronic appearing T12 compression with prior vertebroplasty. There is minimal edema at the posterior superior corner of the T12 vertebral body. Anteriorly there is 50% height loss. Posteriorly there is 5% height loss. Slight retropulsion by 3 mm identified.
Minimal degenerative endplate edema signal at the T9-T10, T3-T5. Chronic Schmorl's nodes identified at T8-T9 with endplate irregularity. Endplate fatty degenerative changes identified.

IMPRESSION:
1. Acute to subacute compression fracture at the superior endplate of T11 with 20% height loss. No retropulsion. No epidural hematoma or ligamentous injury.
2. Chronic compression fracture at T12 with prior vertebroplasty. Minimal edema at the posterior superior corner of T12 is likely from chronic degenerative change or less likely from edema from subacute compression.
3. No significant central canal or foraminal narrowing.

Technique: Multiplanar MRI images of the pelvis with multiphase contrast images and subtraction images

Findings:
Multiple uterine fibroids with dominant fundal intramural/subserosa fibroid and an anterior uterine body intramural/subserosa uterine fibroid. The fundal fibroid measures up to 6.2 cm, is heterogenous on T2, isointense on T1 with uniform enhancement. The anterior uterine body fibroid is T2 dark, T1 isointense with a dark rim, that has possible blooming on GRE images and does not enhance. The peripheral hypointense ring may indicate peripheral calcification, recommend correlation with CT images if available. Additional smaller uterine fibroids.

Myomatous uterus with mild mass effect on the superior bladder.

Multiple Tarlov cyst.

Impression:

Myomatous uterus. No acute pathology

Technique: Multiplanar multisequence MRI of the spine was performed without contrast. 

Findings:
Approximately 50% loss of vertebral body height at T10 with osseous edema throughout the vertebral body, findings consistent with an acute to subacute compression fracture. Approximately 1 mm displacement of the posterior inferior endplate of T10, this mildly deforms the ventral cord without overall canal stenosis. No cord signal abnormality. No foraminal stenosis.  Minimal paraspinal edema noted. 

Elsewhere there is mild scattered chronic appearing vertebral height loss and Schmorl's nodes. Mild reactive/degenerative edema noted in the T3, T4, and L2 vertebral bodies. 

Multilevel degenerative changes noted. Cardiomegaly noted on axial images.

Impression:
1. Acute to subacute compression fracture of T10. Minimal retropulsion without canal or foraminal narrowing. 
2. Chronic and degenerative changes noted elsewhere.

TECHNIQUE:  Multiplanar, multi-sequence MRI of the cervical spine without contrast. 


FINDINGS:

The cervical spine is well aligned.  No abnormal signal is noted in the cervical cord.  Post-surgical changes from anterior fusion of C5 - C7 are appreciated.  Moderate degenerative disc space narrowing is appreciated at C4 - C5.  A broad-based disc bulge at C4 - C5 mildly narrows the thecal sac and both neuroforamina.  A broad-based disc bulge at C6 - C7 moderately narrows the thecal sac, moderately narrows the right neuroforamen and mildly narrows the left neuroforamen.

Technique: Multiplanar multisequence MRI of the cervical spine was performed without contrast. 

Findings:
At C5-C6 there is grade 1 retrolisthesis.

At C6-C7 there is a disc osteophyte complex with uncovertebral hypertrophy. Mild facet and ligamentum flavum hypertrophy. These findings contribute to a moderate severe canal stenosis with cord deformity and equivocal cord signal abnormality. Moderate severe bilateral foraminal narrowing. 

Minimal Modic type 1 endplate change noted at C6/7. Multilevel degenerative changes noted elsewhere. Paraspinal soft tissues unremarkable.  

Impression:
1. Degenerative changes at C6-C7 with a moderate severe canal stenosis with cord deformity and equivocal cord signal abnormality.
2. Grade 1 retrolisthesis at C5-C6. 
Degenerative changes elsewhere as discussed.

Technique: Multisequential multiplanar images obtained of the abdomen with and without IV contrast


Findings:
Liver: The liver contains a nodular contour compatible with cirrhosis. No liver masses. 
Spleen: The spleen is enlarged measuring up to 17.5 cm. 
Gallbladder: There is cholelithiasis. Gallbladder is non distended. No gallbladder wall thickening or adjacent inflammatory change.
Peritoneum: Trace ascites in the right paracolic gutter.


Impression:
Cirrhosis with stigmata of portal hypertension including splenomegaly. No liver masses.
Cholelithiasis.
Trace right paracolic gutter ascites.

Technique: Multiplanar multisequence MRI of the cervical spine was performed without contrast. Susceptibility artifact related to surgical hardware limits the exam. 

Findings:
At C5-C6 there is susceptibility artifact related to surgical hardware which limits the exam at this level. 

At C6-C7 there is mild disc bulge with a superimposed shallow left paracentral protrusion. This mildly deforms the ventral cord without canal or foraminal narrowing. 

Multilevel degenerative changes noted elsewhere. Paraspinal soft tissues unremarkable. Within the limits of the exam, no cord signal abnormality.   

Impression:
1. Shallow left paracentral protrusion at C6-C7 without canal or foraminal narrowing.
2. Susceptibility artifact related to surgical hardware at C5-C6 limits the exam in this region.
3. Multilevel degenerative changes elsewhere.

Technique: CT of the Chest without contrast.

Findings: 
Mild cardiomegaly. Prosthetic aortic valve. No thoracic aorta aneurysm. Mild calcific atherosclerosis of the aortic arch and descending thoracic aorta. 

Impression:
- Mild cardiomegaly.
- Prosthetic aortic valve.
- No thoracic aorta aneurysm.

Technique:
Multiplanar, multisequence MRI of the abdomen with and without contrast. 
Findings:
Cirrhotic morphology of the liver with nodular contour and recanalization of the umbilical vein. There is an arterially hyperenhancing 1.4 cm lesion in segment 2 that does not demonstrate washout although evaluation is limited given the location of the lesion. However, there is T2 intermediate intensity lesion in segment 4A which demonstrates persistent peripheral enhancement throughout the postcontrast phases of imaging as well as diffusion restriction. This lesion measures approximately 5.0 x 3.5 cm. There is associated branching foci with the left hepatic lobe and small collections with diffusion restriction and peripheral enhancement. The left portal vein does not opacify and is occluded. Prominent periportal lymph nodes are noted.

Sequelae of portal hypertension with splenomegaly and small volume ascites.

Impression:
1.  Cirrhotic morphology of the liver with sequelae of portal hypertension, including splenomegaly and ascites.
2.  LI-RADs 3 lesion in segment 2 measuring 1.4 cm.
3.  Left portal vein occlusion.  Adjacent peripherally enhancing focus in segment 4A which may reflect tumor thrombus vs a cholangiocarcinoma primary.  Associated infectious process with small abscesses in the left hepatic lobe. Short term follow up is recommended to assess for interval changes.

Technique: Axial CT of the thoracic spine was obtained without intravenous contrast with coronal and sagittal reconstructions.

Findings:
Grade 1 anterolisthesis T1 on T2.  Trace anterolisthesis T2 on T3.

No acute compression fracture.  Multilevel mild degenerative changes with intervertebral disc space narrowing and endplate osteophytes.

Anterior spinal fusion hardware are C5-C6  Advanced intervertebral disc spce narrowing at C6-C7.

Aortic calcifications.  Respiratory atelectasis.

Impression:
Mild degenerative changes of the thoracic spine with grade 1 anterolisthesis T1 on T2 and trace anterolisthesis T2 on T3.

Technique:

Technique: CT examination of the abdomen was performed before and after administration of intravenous contrast.

Findings: Nodular, shrunken cirrhotic liver morphology with relative hypertrophy of the left hepatic lobe and caudate lobe. There is a large heterogeneously arterially enhancing mass involving the right hepatic lobe which measures approximately 11.7 x 7.6 cm in transaxial dimensions. The mass demonstrates washout on the portal venous phase images. There is non-opacification of the right portal vein. On the arterial phase images there is also heterogenous enhancement in the expected course of the right portal vein which is difficult to delineate from and possibly contiguous with the aforementioned liver mass. There is a dilated branching hypoenhancing structure in the posterior right hepatic lobe concerning portal vein occlusion. There are additional small caliber branching hypoenhancing structures in the periphery of the right hepatic lobe which likely represent dilated intrahepatic bile ducts. 

Recanalized umbilical vein. Perigastric and perisplenic varices. 

There is splenomegaly, with the enlarged spleen measuring up to 16.5 cm in craniocaudal dimension. 

Small volume ascites.

There are small bilateral non-obstructing kidney stones. The largest of which include a 5 mm stone in the right lower pole and a 3 mm stone in the left lower pole. No hydronephrosis.

There is a small avidly, arterially enhancing, exophytic mass along the greater curvature of the distal stomach, which measures 1.3 cm. 

Impression: 
1. Large right hepatic lobe mass highly suspicious for hepatocellular carcinoma. 
2. Indeterminate tumor in vein involving the right portal vein. Recommend contrast enhanced MRI of the abdomen for further characterization. 
3. Cirrhosis and sequelae of portal hypertension including splenomegaly, ascites and upper abdominal varices.
4. Exophytic, avidly enhancing 1.3 cm mass along the stomach suspicious for a GIST tumor. Differential diagnosis also includes metastasis in the setting of suspected liver malignancy as well as other neoplasms such as neuroendocrine tumor.

Hepatic lesion compatible with a hemangioma.

CLINICAL INFORMATION:
Fatty liver, Cholelithiasis, Renal cyst, Urolithiasis

TECHNIQUE: CT of the abdomen and pelvis with and without IV contrast. No enteric contrast
administered. CT IVP protocol was performed.


LIVER: Liver is normal in size and smooth contour. Indeterminate hypoenhancing 1.1cm lesion in segment 8, that is isoattenuating on delayed phases. Mild hypoattenuation of the liver relative to the spleen. 

GALLBLADDER AND BILE DUCTS: Layering density in the gallbladder reflecting sludge vs tiny stones. No biliary ductal dilatation.

KIDNEYS AND URETERS: 
Kidneys are symmetric in size, cortical thickness, and enhancement. Simple cyst of the left mid-pole, no dedicated imaging follow-up is recommended. No suspicious renal lesion. 

Non-obstructing right lower pole calculus measuring 1.2 cm. 
No right-sided hydronephrosis or hydroureter.

Mild pelvocaliectasis of the left extrarenal pelvis, with a 1.2 cm calculus at the left extrarenal pelvis/ureteric junction and urothelial enhancement. There are additional nephrolithiasis in the left lower pole measuring up to 1.0 cm.  Nonspecific bilateral perinephric fat stranding. 

Delayed excretion of contrast in the left kidney relative to the left. There is mild left hydroureter and periureteral fatty stranding along the entire course. 


BLADDER: Moderately well distended and opacified with layering contrast. No suspicious filling defects. Suggestion of circumferential wall thickening. 

IMPRESSION:
	1. Mildly obstructive left kidney stone measuring 1.2 cm causing mild pelvocaliectasis/hydronephrosis. There is delayed excretion of contrast, with associated periureteral fatty stranding along the course of the mildly left ureter. 
	2. Circumferential wall thickening of the bladder, recommend correlation of signs/symptoms of cystitis. 
	3. Additional non-obstructive right nephrolithiasis, without hydroureter or hydronephrosis. 
	4. Indeterminate segment 8 hepatic lesion, can consider outpatient liver mass protocol CT/MRI, or contrast enhanced ultrasound. 
	5. Mild hepatic steatosis.
	6. Cholelithiasis without evidence of cholecystitis.

Technique:
CT abdomen and pelvis with IV contrast, portal venous phase.  Multiplanar reformats.

Findings:
3.7 x 2.9 cm heterogeneously hypervascular mass centered in the caudate lobe of the liver near the confluence of the hepatic veins.  The majority of the mass demonstrates avid enhancement with several nodular and bandlike areas of relative hypoenhancement.  Also a separate 13 mm homogeneously hypervascular lesion in segment IV near the middle hepatic vein.

Impression:
1.  Heterogeneously hypervascular mass centered in the caudate lobe of the liver.  The enhancement pattern is indeterminate on a single phase of contrast, and differential consideration include lesions such as a hemangioma, adenoma, or focal nodular hyperplasia.  Hepatocellular carcinoma could also have this apperance, particularly if there is a history of cirrhosis or other hepatic risk factors.  Suggest dedicated liver protocol multiphasic CT or MRI for further characterization.

2.  Another small, homogeneously hypervascular lesion in segment IV of the liver is also nonspecific but may reflect a small hemangioma or shunt.  Suggest attention to this on follow-up imaging as well.

TECHNIQUE: 
Noncontrast chest CT was obtained. 


FINDINGS: 
There is mild scattered emphysema with a centrilobular component in the right upper lobe and mixed paraseptal/centrilobular components in the left upper lobe.  There is mild hyperinflation in keeping with air trapping. 


IMPRESSION: 
Mild scattered emphysema with centrilobular and paraseptal components as well as air trapping.

Findings: Ascending aortic ectasia measures 4cm at the level of the main pulmonary artery. The aortic root measures 4.1 cm at the level of the sinuses of Valsalva.  Assessment for dissection and patency is limited without contrast.

Impression: Mild aortic root and ascending aortic ectasia.  A CTA or MRA of the chest is recommended every 12 months.

Indication: None

technique: Routine multiplanar, multisequential enhanced MR of the cervical spine was obtained before and after the administration of intravenous contrast.

Findings:

Left central disc protrusion at C3-C4 slightly indents the left ventral cord, resulting in mild spinal canal stenosis and mild left neuroforaminal narrowing. 

No cord signal abnormality.

Impression:

Left central C3-C4 disc protrusion which indents the left ventral cord, resulting in mild spinal canal stenosis and mild left neuroforaminal narrowing.

No cord edema.

Technique: Routine CT of the chest was obtained without the administration of intravenous contrast. Coronal and sagittal reformats were acquired, as well as high resolution axial images using lung windows. 

Technique:

There is a lesion in the right posterior aspect of the T8 vertebral body, which demonstrates a corduroy appearance on the sagittal view, reflecting thickened trabeculations. The axial view of the lesions shows a "polka dot" appearance, also reflecting thickened trabeculations. No cortical defects or evidence of extraosseous extension.The lesion slightly extends to the right pedicle. No involvement of the left vertebral arch/posterior elements.

Impression: 

Findings compatible with benign vertebral hemangioma without aggressive features.

Technique: CT of the abdomen and pelvis performed in the portal phase. CT of the pelvis also performed in the delayed phase.

Findings:
In the right adnexa and arising from  the right ovary, there is a 1.6 cm circumscribed hypodense lesion that demonstrates attenuation between 0 HU and 20 HU. The lesion is uniform in density and appearance. There are no associated calcifications, measurable mural nodularity, or perceptible thick internal calcifications.

In the right lower quadrant at the base of the cecum, there are multiple metallic clips and the appendix is also not visualized. The findings are compatible with postoperative changes of prior appendectomy.

Impression:
1. A 1.6 cm right ovarian cyst.
2. Postoperative changes of prior appendectomy.

TECHNIQUE: Axial CT of the chest without IV contrast with multiplanar reformats

FINDINGS:
Moderate pericardial effusion anteriorly, with simple attenuation. No pericardial calcifications.

IMPRESSION:
Moderate pericardial effusion. Cardiac echo may be considered for further evaluation.

TECHNIQUE: Noncontrast CT of the head

FINDINGS:

No acute intracranial hemorrhage, midline shift, or acute loss of gray-white differentiation.

Extensive encephalomalacia in the right temporal lobe, temporal operculum, insula, subinsular region, and external capsule. There is associated pronounced ex vacuo dilatation of the temporal horn of the right lateral ventricle.

Encephalomalacia is also seen in the anteroinferior left temporal lobe, with associated ex vacuo dilatation of the temporal horn of the left lateral ventricle.

Patchy hypoattenuation within the subcortical and periventricular white matter.

Mild generalized parenchymal volume loss. No evidence of acute hydrocephalus. Intact basilar cisterns.

Right lens implant.

Small bilateral mastoid effusions.

No significant paranasal sinus disease within the included field of view.

Atheromatous calcification along the bilateral carotid siphons.

IMPRESSION:

1. No acute intracranial findings.

2. Extensive right MCA territory encephalomalacia, most pronounced in the temporal lobe, consistent with an old right MCA territory infarct.

3. Encephalomalacia is also seen in the left temporal lobe, consistent with an old left MCA territory infarct. 

4. Patchy hypoattenuation within the subcortical and periventricular white matter, which likely represents chronic small vessel disease.

Indication: Fatty liver

Technique: Non contrast CT abdomen and pelvis.

Findings: The liver demonstrates diffuse low attenuation.  No suspicious mass or cirrhosis is seen though evaluation is limited without contrast.

Impression: Hepatic steatosis.

Technique: CT images of abdomen and pelvis were obtained without IV contrast. Multiplanar reformats obtained. 


Findings:
Kidneys: Multiple bilateral simple renal cysts (measure 2 HU), the largest of which measures approximately 2.3cm and is located in the mid right renal pole. Left upper pole hyperdense well circumscribed lesion measuring approximately 1cm which may reflect a hemorrhagic cyst. No renal calculi or hydronephrosis. 


Impression:
Multiple bilateral simple renal cysts. Left upper pole hyperdense lesion which may reflect a hemorrhagic cyst. A renal US may be obtained for further evaluation

Technique: CT scan of the chest without IV contrast.

Findings:
Minimal biapical scarring. Few tiny scattered micronodules in bilateral lungs.Bilateral lungs are otherwise unremarkable. No consolidation, pleural effusion or pneumothorax. Trachea and major bronchi are normal.
No enlarged mediastinal or hilar lymph nodes. 
Normal cardiac size. Coronary artery calcifications. 
Non obstructive left nephrolithiasis in the upper pole measuring 17mm. Small hepatic calcification in the left lobe.
Cholecystectomy clip.
Thoracic spine degenerative changes with multilevel osteophytes and disc space narrowing of lower thoracic vertebrae.

Impression: 
1. Minimal biapical scarring. 
2. Few nonspecific tiny scattered micronodules in bilateral lungs, likely sequelae of prior infection or inflammation.
Non obstructive left nephrolithiasis.

TECHNIQUE: CT of the abdomen/pelvis was obtained in axial view with intravenous contrast.

FINDINGS:

Small pericardial effusion measuring 9 mm in thickness. No CT evidence of tamponade. 

There is an ill-defined subtle hypodensity of the hepatic dome measuring up to 2.5 cm (mean HU of 88).

There is a tubular shaped hypodensity of hepatic segment 7. 

The caudal aspect of the liver is not included within the images obtained. 

Examination is essentially non-diagnostic for evaluation of spondylolisthesis as several images of the thoracolumbar spine are not included and no coronal or sagittal images/reformats provided.

IMPRESSION:
Small pericardial effusion.

Ill-defined hypodensity of the hepatic dome, which could represent perfusional changes.

Tubular hypodensity of segment 7 likely represents a dilated bile duct.

Non-diagnostic examination for evaluation of spondylolisthesis and for caudal aspect of liver given images obtained.

Indication: none

Technique: 
CT images of the abdomen were obtained after the administration of intravenous contrast.  Multiplanar reformatted images were provided. Oral contrast was also administered. 

Findings: 
Lung bases: The lung bases are clear. No consolidations or pleural effusions.  Partially visualized mild coronary artery calcifications. 
Hepatobiliary: The liver is unremarkable. The hepatic vasculature is patent. Cholelithiasis is noted without evidence of acute cholecystitis. 
Pancreas: There is fatty atrophy of the pancreas. No pancreatic masses or pancreatic ductal dilation.
Spleen: Unremarkable.
Adrenal glands: Unremarkable.
Kidneys: There is no hydronephrosis of nephrolithiasis noted bilaterally. 
Bowel: The patient is status post gastric banding with reservoir noted within the soft tissues of the right lower quadrant. The gastric band is appropriately positioned without evidence of complication. No bowel obstruction.  The appendix is unremarkable. Oral contrast is noted to the level of the ascending colon. 
Abdominal and pelvic lymph nodes: No lymphadenopathy.    
Peritoneum: No ascites.    
Vasculature: No abdominal aortic aneurysm. 
Musculoskeletal system and soft tissue: No aggressive osseous lesion.  Age indeterminate compression deformity of the L5 vertebral body with approximately 30% vertebral body height loss.  

Impression:
Cholelithiasis is noted without evidence of acute cholecystitis.
Age indeterminate compression deformity of the L5 vertebral body with approximately 30% vertebral body height loss.

Technique: CT of the abdomen and pelvis with IV and oral contrast.    

Findings:  

Severe cardiomegaly partially imaged.  No pericardial effusion.  Mild left basilar linear atelectasis or scarring.  

Impression:  

Severe cardiomegaly.

Technique: CT of the Chest without contrast.

Findings: Very mild cylindrical bronchiectasis. No mucous plugs. No significant emphysema. No focal mass or consolidation. No pleural effusion. Cholelithiasis. No gallbladder mural thickening or pericholecystic fluid. No biliary ductal dilatation.

Impression:
- Very mild cylindrical bronchiectasis.
- Cholelithiasis. No evidence of acute cholecystitis.

Indication: Fatty Liver.

Technique: CT of the abdomen and pelvis with intravenous contrast.

Findings: There is diffuse low attenuation of the liver. No suspicious masses are seen.  The portal vein is patent.

Impression: Hepatic steatosis.

TECHNIQUE: Multi-phasic axial CT of the Abdomen it was performed before and after intravenous contrast administration, including non-contrast, arterial, portal venous, and delayed face imaging. Additionally, oral contrast was administered.

FINDINGS: 
The liver is normal in size and contour. There is homogeneous parenchymal enhancement with no focal lesions. The portal veins are patent. The hepatic arteries are patent. There is no re-canalization of the umbilical vein. There is no evidence of esophageal or gastric varices.

There are surgical clips in the gallbladder bed.

IMPRESSION:
1. Normal size and contour of the liver with no evidence of cirrhosis.
2. Status post cholecystectomy.

Technique: CT of the Chest without contrast.

Findings: 1.7 x 1.6 x 1.7 cm spiculated nodule in the posterior right lower lobe with mild associated pleural retraction. No additional pulmonary nodules or masses. No mediastinal or hilar lymphadenopathy. No bronchiectasis. No pleural effusion.

Impression:
- 1.7 x 1.6 x 1.7 cm spiculated nodule in the posterior right lower lobe with mild associated pleural retraction. This is concerning for malignancy and further evaluation with PET-CT and/or biopsy is recommended.

Indication: None

Technique: Multiplanar, multiphasic CT of the abdomen was obtained before and after the administration of intravenous contrast in both the arterial and venous phase.

Findings:

Unilocular simple cyst in the upper pole left kidney which is partially exophytic, resulting in slight mass effect on the greater curvature of the stomach. 

Cholecystectomy clips. Metallic stent within the common bile duct. Gas within the intrahepatic and extrahepatic biliary tree consistent with pneumobilia. No biliary ductal dilation. Mild pancreatic ductal dilation in the pancreatic body. 

Impression:

Benign simple cyst (Bosniak I) in the upper pole left kidney which is slightly exophytic, resulting in slight mass effect on the greater curvature of the stomach.

TECHNIQUE: 
Multiplanar, multisequence noncontrast brain MRI was performed. 

FINDINGS: 
There is patchy periventricular T2/FLAIR hyperintensity in addition to scattered small foci within the subcortical and deep hemispheric white matter, which is nonspecific but likely reflects moderate chronic microvascular ischemia. There is no acute or early subacute infarct. 

IMPRESSION: 
Moderate chronic microvascular ischemia without acute infarct.

Technique:
CT abdomen and pelvis without contrast.
Findings:
There is a cirrhotic morphology of the liver with nodular contour and widening of the fissures. There are multiple nonspecific heterogenously hypodense lesions with the one  in segment 7 measuring 3.9 cm and the one in segment 6 measuring 5.4 cm. Additional wedge shaped hypodense focus is noted in the hepatic dome. 

There is a heterogenous lesion in the body of the pancreas measuring up to 3.8 cm.

Splenomengaly with the spleen measuring 15.5 cm in the AP dimension. Perisplenic varices are noted including a splenorenal shunt.

No ascites.

Impression:
Cirrhotic morphology of the liver with nonspecific lesions as described above. Further evaluation with CT or MRI liver protocol is recommended.
Sequelae of portal hypertension with splenomegaly and varices including a splenorenal shunt.
Nonspecific heterogenous lesion in the body of the pancreas. This can additionally be further characterized on follow up imaging.

TECHNIQUE: 
Multiple sagittal and axial MR sequences of the lumbar spine without IV contrast. 

FINDINGS:
Preserved lumbar lordosis. No spondylolisthesis. L3 vertebral body hemangioma. L5-S1 facet arthropathy results in mild right and moderate left neuroforaminal stenosis. The paraspinal soft tissues are normal. 

IMPRESSION:
L5-S1 facet arthropathy results in mild right and moderate left neuroforaminal stenosis.

TECHNIQUE:
Contrast-enhanced CT of the chest was performed.

FINDINGS:
There is moderate, scattered, mixed centrilobular and paraseptal emphysema, notably involving the upper lobes and superior segments of both lower lobes. Mild hyperinflation is seen, in keeping with air trapping. A mosaic attenuation of the pulmonary parenchyma is present, reflecting small airways disease.

IMPRESSION:
Moderate mixed centrilobular and paraseptal emphysema.
Hyperinflation, in keeping with air trapping.
Mosaic attenuation of the pulmonary parenchyma, reflecting small airways disease.

Technique: Noncontrast chest CT with axial coronal and sagittal reformatted images.  Additional thin axial and MIP reformatted images were provided.

Findings: Upper lobe predominant emphysema appears moderate to severe in extent, with centrilobular and paraseptal components.  There is no concerning nodule, mass, or consolidation within the lungs.  A small amount of debris is noted within the bronchus intermedius and within the trachea. Very minimal lower lung atelectasis.  No pleural abnormality.

Thoracic aorta is normal in course and caliber with mild atherosclerotic calcification.  Main pulmonary artery is mildly dilated at 3.4 cm which could reflect pulmonary arterial hypertension.  Heart size within normal limits with significant coronary artery calcification.  No discrete adenopathy.  No concerning bone lesion or evidence of fracture.

No acute findings in the imaged upper abdomen.  Cholelithiasis incidentally noted with decompressed appearance of the gallbladder.

Impression: 
Moderate to severe upper lobe predominant emphysema.  Tiny amount of debris within the large central airway.
No concerning nodule, mass or consolidation.
Mild dilation of the main pulmonary artery could reflect pulmonary arterial hypertension.

Technique: 
Multiphase CT images of the abdomen and pelvis were obtained before and after the administration of intravenous contrast.  Multiplanar reformatted images were provided. 

Findings: 
Kidneys: There is a 1.0 x 1.0 x 0.8cm simple renal cyst (mean Hounsfield units - 19) in the left midpole. There is no hydronephrosis or nephrolithiasis bilaterally. No solid renal masses. 

Impression:
1.0 cm simple cyst within the left midpole

Indication: Uterine fibroids.

Technique: Contrast enhanced CT abdomen and pelvis.

Findings: A hypoattenuating anterior subserosal uterine mass likely represents a fibroid. It measures 3.7 x 3 cm.  No additional masses are seen. The endometrium is within normal limits.

Impression: Single subserosal uterine mass likely represents a fibroid.

Technique: CT of the abdomen and pelvis with coronal and sagittal reformatted images provided

Findings: 
Lung bases: There is a nodule in the left lower lobe measuring 10 mm. Pacemaker leads are noted within the right atrium and right ventricle.  The imaged portion of the heart is within normal limits of size.

Abdomen: Several small hepatic hypodensities are indeterminate, possibly cysts.  Gallbladder unremarkable.  Pancreas is unremarkable.  Spleen unremarkable.  Adrenal glands unremarkable.  Kidneys appear normal without hydronephrosis, concerning lesion or discrete stone.  Ureters are nondilated.  The urinary bladder is not fully distended though the wall appears thickened, cystitis is difficult to exclude in the correct clinical setting.  The abdominal aorta is moderately calcified and ectatic measuring up to 2.8 cm along the infrarenal segment.  A stent is noted within the right common iliac artery.

Small hiatal hernia.  Stomach otherwise unremarkable.  There is no evidence of bowel obstruction or bowel inflammation.  Normal appendix is visualized.  The colon is unremarkable containing a mild fecal load.  The prostate is enlarged measuring 6.3 cm in transverse dimension.  No discrete adenopathy.

Bones: Partially visualized midline sternotomy wires.  No concerning lytic or blastic osseous lesion.  Left hip arthroplasty appears uncomplicated.  Degenerative disc disease most pronounced at L2-3 level.

Impression:

1.  Thickening of the urinary bladder wall could reflect cystitis or trabeculation in the setting of prostatomegaly.  Correlate for symptoms of bladder outlet obstruction.

2.  Nodule measuring 10 mm in the left lower lobe.

3.  Infrarenal abdominal aorta up to 2.8 cm.

TECHNIQUE: Routine noncontrast CT of the chest was performed.

FINDINGS:

Examination of the chest shows an enlarged cardiac silhouette.  There is broad-necked protrusion of the left ventricular apex, consistent with a left ventricular aneurysm.  The thoracic aorta is normal in caliber.  The pulmonary arteries are normal in caliber.  No pericardial effusion.

IMPRESSION:
Cardiomegaly.
Bulging of the left ventricular apex, consistent with left ventricular aneurysm, typically secondary to myocardial infarction.

TECHNIQUE: Axial multiphase CT of the abdomen and pelvis without and with contrast with multiplanar reformats. Delayed images of the abdomen and pelvis also obtained.

FINDINGS:
Left proximal ureteral stone measuring 2mm.
No hydronephrosis or hydroureter. 

Hepatic steatosis. No focal lesion. 

IMPRESSION:
1. Left proximal ureteral stone measuring 2mm. No hydronephrosis or hydroureter. 
2. Hepatic steatosis.

TECHNIQUE: Axial CT of the abdomen and pelvis with IV and oral contrast with multiplanar reformats.

FINDINGS:
The uterus is enlarged and lobulated with multiple heterogeneous uterine masses with calcifications. The overall extent is 9.7 x 8.1 x 6.3 cm. 

IMPRESSION:
Multiple calcified uterine fibroids. Further evaluation may be obtained with pelvic ultrasound or MRI if clinically indicated.

Technique: Axial CT images of the abdomen and pelvis was obtained before and after the administration of intravenous contrast.  Oral contrast was also administrated. Multiplanar reformats were obtained. 

FINDINGS:

Normal gallbladder without gallstones. No pericholecystic fluid or gallbladder wall thickening. No intrahepatic or extrahepatic biliary ductal dilation.

There is a 16 x 19 mm cyst in the upper pole of the right kidney. Similarly, 16 x 15 mm cyst in the upper pole of the left kidney. Excreted contrast within the collecting system and urinary bladder. No hydronephrosis or renal stones. No suspicions renal lesions.
 
Moderate cardiomegaly. Partial visualization of pacemakers leads.  No pericardial or pleural effusions. 

IMPRESSION: 
1.	Moderate cardiomegaly. 
2.	Bilateral renal cyst as detailed above. No suspicions renal lesions.

Technique: Routine unenhanced CT of the chest was obtained with both coronal and sagittal reformats. 

Findings:

Punctate hyperdensity in the lower pole left kidney compatible with nonobstructing renal calculus.

Cortical thinning of the upper pole left kidney compatible with atrophy. No perinephric fat stranding of fluid collections. Dilation of the adjacent renal collecting system reflects moderate hydronephrosis.  No obstructing left renal calculus.

No left hydroureter or ureteral calculus. 

No right hydronephrosis or urolithiasis. 

Impression: 

Findings compatible with chronic hydronephrosis in the upper pole left kidney with cortical atrophy. 

Punctate nonobstructing left renal calculus. No obstructing left renal or ureteral calculus.

Indication: Aortic aneurysm, Fatty liver.

Technique: Contrast enhanced CT of the chest.

Findings: The ascending aorta at the level of the main pulmonary artery measures 4.1cm. The aortic root at the level of the sinuses of Valsalva measures 3.8cm.  No aortic dissection is seen.  The liver demonstrates diffusely low attenuation suggesting steatosis.

Impression: Mild ascending aortic ectasia measuring 4.1cm. A repeat CTA or MRA of the chest every 12 months is recommended. Hepatic steatosis.

Technique:   

Multi-detector CT Imaging of theabdomen and pelvis. Intravenous and contrast were utilized. Multiplanar reconstructions. 

Findings:

There is a 1.9 x 1.9 cm complex, circumscribed low density lesion in the anteromedial aspect of the mid to upper pole of the left kidney.  Appearance and density measurements are not compatible with a simple cyst.  Left renal vein is patent.  Additional too small to characterize tiny low density lesion in the lower pole of the left kidney.

There is no evidence of hydronephrosis or ureteral calculus.  There are at least 4 small nonobstucting calculi within the right kidney, measuring up to 3 mm.  There are at least 3 nonobstructing left renal calculi, measuring up to 3 mm in diameter as well.  


Impression:

Complex 1.9 cm low density lesion in the left kidney.  This may represent a complex cyst or solid lesion, such as renal cell carcinoma.  Recommend further evaluation with renal mass protocol CT or MRI with and without contrast for further evaluation.  Renal ultrasound would also be helpful in characterizing this lesion.

Bilateral nonobstructing nephrolithiasis.  No hydronephrosis or ureteral calculus.

TECHNIQUE: CT abdomen and pelvis without IV contrast and with oral contrast.  Multiplanar reformats.

FINDINGS: There is a punctate, less than 2mm, calcific density within a right renal interpolar calyx.  There is no obstruction or hydronephrosis.

There is aortic atherosclerosis, as well as a retroaortic left renal vein.

Calcified phleboliths within the pelvis.

IMPRESSION: Nonobstructing punctate right interpolar calyceal calculus.

Indication: None

Technique: Multiplanar, multisequential MR of the brain was obtained without the administration of intravenous contrast.

Findings: 

No restricted diffusion to suggest acute infarction.

Scattered foci of susceptibility artifact in the supratentorial and infratentorial compartment, consistent with chronic microhemorrhage. 


Confluent T2/FLAIR hyperintense signal abnormality in the periventricular supratentorial white matter bilaterally is nonspecific, but most consistent with moderate chronic microvascular ischemic changes. 

Moderate cerebral atrophy with proportional ventricular enlargment. Marked asymmetrical enlargement of the left lateral ventricle with asymmetric prominence of the left sylvian fissure, consistent with ex vacuo dilation and marked left hemisphere volume loss. 

Bilateral hippocampal atrophy. 

Impression:

No acute intracranial abnormality.

Cerebral volume loss with marked involvement of the left cerebral hemisphere. 

Bilateral hippocampal atrophy which is suggestive of neurodegenerative disease.

Technique: CT of the Chest without contrast.

Findings: Mild centrilobular and paraseptal emphysema with an upper lobe predominance. No significant bronchiectasis. No pleural effusion. Normal heart size. No pericardial effusion. Mild ectasia of ascending thoracic aorta, measuring 3.6 cm. Mild calcific atherosclerosis of the thoracic aorta. Diffuse hepatic steatosis.

Impression:
- Mild centrilobular and paraseptal emphysema with an upper lobe predominance.
- Mild ectasia of the ascending thoracic aorta, measuring 3.6 cm.
- Diffuse hepatic steatosis.

Technique:

Multidetector CT images of the abdomen and pelvis were obtained after the administration of intravenous contrast. Multiplanar reformats submitted.

Findings:

Osseous demineralization. 

Bilateral acute mildly displaced L5 transverse process fractures. 

Acute sacral fracture with vertical extension through the bilateral sacral ala and transverse extension across the S2 sacral segment. 

Remodeling of the sacral canal at the S2 segment likely reflecting an underlying tarlov cyst. 

Lumbar vertebral body heights are preserved. Moderate multilevel degenerative disc changes of the lumbar spine with mild central canal stenoses. 

Aortoiliac atherosclerotic calcifications. 

Impression:
1. Acute bilateral L5 transverse process fractures. 
2. Acute sacral fracture. 
3. Degenerative disc changes of the lumbar spine with mild central canal stenoses.

TECHNIQUE: CT of the chest was obtained without contrast. Multiplanar reformats were submitted.

FINDINGS:
There is mild to moderate upper lobe predominant centrilobular emphysema.

Findings: Mild cardiomegaly. No pericardial effusion. Mild-to-moderate aortic valve calcifications. 5.3 x 5.0 cm ascending thoracic aorta aneurysm. No aortic dissection. Moderate-sized hiatal hernia.

Impression:
- Mild cardiomegaly.
- 5.3 x 5.0 cm ascending thoracic aorta aneurysm.
- Mild-to-moderate aortic valve calcifications.
- Moderate-sized hiatal hernia.

Technique:  Multiplanar, multisequence MRI of the lumbar spine without IV contrast

Findings:
There is a broad-based disc bulge at the level of L3-4 resulting in mild spinal canal narrowing.  There is moderate right and mild to moderate neuroforaminal narrowing at this level.  There is also bilateral facet hypertrophy at this level.

There is also a subtle disc bulge at the level of L4-5.  

Impression:
Disc bulge at L3-4 and facet hypertrophy resulting in mild spinal canal narrowing and bilateral neuroforaminal narrowing at this level as described.

Subtle disc bulge at the level of L4-5.

TECHNIQUE: 
Multiplanar, multisequence noncontrast brain MRI was obtained. 


FINDINGS: 
There is transcortical encephalomalacia and gliosis is involving the left frontal lobe with involvement of the frontal operculum, insular cortex and subinsular white matter in keeping with remote anterior division left MCA transcortical infarct.  Hemosiderin staining is seen along the cortex in keeping with a remote hemorrhagic component. Ex vacuo dilatation of the left lateral ventricle is seen reflecting the volume loss. 

There is slit-like encephalomalacia and gliosis involving the left lentiform nucleus with surrounding hemosiderin staining in keeping with a remote hypertensive hemorrhage or a remote hemorrhagic infarct. 

There is superimposed patchy areas of T2/FLAIR hyperintensity within the supratentorial subcortical, deep hemispheric and periventricular white matter which is nonspecific but likely reflects mild chronic microvascular ischemia. 


IMPRESSION: 
Remote anterior division left MCA transcortical infarct with hemosiderin staining reflecting a remote hemorrhagic component. 

Slit-like encephalomalacia with surrounding hemosiderin staining in the left lentiform nucleus which may reflect remote hypertensive hemorrhage or a remote hemorrhagic infarct. 

Mild chronic microvascular ischemia. 

No acute infarct.

TECHNIQUE: CT Abdomen and Pelvis with oral and IV contrast
FINDINGS: 
Small bilateral pleural effusions are noted, greater on the right side.
There is a subcentimeter hypodense lesion in the left hepatic lobe which is too small to characterize.
There is mesenteric and retroperitoneal adenopathy.
Omental caking and peritoneal implants are noted.
There is moderate amount of partially loculated ascites.

IMPRESSION:
Abdominal adenopathy, omental caking/peritoneal carcinomatosis and moderate-sized loculated ascites likely reflecting malignancy/metastatic disease.
Small bilateral pleural effusions.

Technique: A lumbar spine MRI examination was performed in the sagittal and axial planes without intravenous contrast.  Multiple pulse sequences were obtained.  

Findings: 
L4-L5- Normal disc signal intensity and height. Disc bulge with left foraminal disc protrusion. No central canal stenosis. No right neural foraminal narrowing. Mild left neural foraminal narrowing. The disc encroaches on the exiting left L5 nerve root. Normal facet joints.

L5-S1 Normal disc signal intensity and height. Disc bulge with shallow disc protrusion. No central canal stenosis. No neural foraminal narrowing. Normal facet joints. 

Impression:
L4-L5 disc bulge with left foraminal disc herniation. 
L5-S1 disc bulge with shallow disc protrusion.

Technique: 
CT images of the abdomen were obtained after the administration of intravenous contrast.  Multiplanar reformatted images were provided. 

Findings: 
Liver: Mild diffuse hepatic steatosis with decreased attenuation of the liver when compared to the spleen (mean hepatic Hounsfield units 92). No hepatic masses. The Hepatic vasculature is patent. No nodularity of the hepatic capsule to suggest cirrhosis. 
Spleen: The spleen is unremarkable (mean splenic Hounsfield units 111)

Impression:
Diffuse hepatic steatosis.

Technique: Post contrast multiplanar CT images of the chest are obtained using a PE protocol. Coronal and sagittal MIP images are included. 

Findings:
1. Moderate sized pleural effusions are seen bilaterally.
2. No evidence of pulmonary embolism is seen by CT criteria.
3. No acute infiltrates or pulmonary masses are identified. 
4. Mild cardiomegaly is seen.
5. Mild atherosclerotic changes are seen involving the descending thoracic aorta. Coarse atherosclerotic calcification is seen at the origin of the left common carotid artery. 


IMPRESSION:
1. No evidence of pulmonary embolism by CT criteria. 
2. Bilateral pleural effusions are present.
3. Mild cardiomegaly is seen. 
4. Mild atherosclerotic changes are seen involving the descending thoracic aorta. Coarse atherosclerotic calcification is seen at the origin of the left common carotid artery.

TECHNIQUE: 
CT of the abdomen and pelvis was performed before and after IV contrast.  Postcontrast imaging was obtained during the nephrographic and urographic phases.  Coronal reformatted images were created. 


FINDINGS: 
Bilateral renal cortical and parapelvic cysts are present.  Parapelvic cysts cause mild mass effect upon the intrarenal collecting system, left greater than right.  In the lateral right midpole renal cortex, there is a hyperdense renal lesion measuring 30 HU measuring 1.4 by 0.9 cm but without significant enhancement.  This is most in keeping with a hemorrhagic cyst with a fine internal septation.  Additional simple cysts are scattered throughout the right kidney many of which are parapelvic in location.  For example, a dominant midpole parapelvic cyst measures 3.2 by 1.8 by 2.1 cm.  In the right lower pole a simple parapelvic cyst measures 2.3 by 1.9 by 1.8 cm.  Additional smaller parapelvic and cortical cysts are present in the right kidney.  In the left kidney, multiple parapelvic cysts are seen, including a dominant midpole cyst measuring 4.6 by 4.2 by 4.7 cm.  Cortical cysts are seen, including an exophytic lower pole simple cyst measuring 2.8 by 2.6 by 3.5 cm.  In the anterior lower pole cortex, a cyst with a thin internal septation measures 1.7 by 1.8 by 1.8 cm.  Multiple additional parapelvic and cortical cysts are present. 


IMPRESSION: 
Bilateral renal cortical and parapelvic cysts the majority of which are simple although a 1.4 cm right midpole renal cortical hemorrhagic cyst is present in addition to a left lower pole renal cyst with a thin internal septation.

Technique: CT of the abdomen and pelvis was performed after the administration of intravenous contrast. Oral contrast was administered. Delayed phase images were also obtained. 

Findings: Low density appearance of the liver which may suggest hepatic steatosis however technically incompletely evaluated on this exam.  Colon diverticulosis without evidence of diverticulitis. Right breast density with multiple surrounding surgical clips. Area of fat density irregularity in the left breast, possibly fat necrosis, however incompletely characterized. Degenerative changes of the spine.

Impression: No acute findings in the abdomen or pelvis. Low density appearance of the liver which may suggest hepatic steatosis however technically incompletely evaluated on this exam.

TECHNIQUE: 
Multiplanar, multisequence MRI of the pelvis was performed. 


FINDINGS: 
There is a severe remote benign osteoporotic L4 compression fracture without osseous edema. 

There is a moderate remote benign osteoporotic L5 compression fracture without significant retropulsion or osseous edema.  Low signal intensity is seen along the superior endplate, which may reflect methylmethacrylate related to vertebral augmentation or sclerosis. 

There is discogenic, endplate and facet degeneration in the lower lumbar spine. 


IMPRESSION: 
Severe remote benign osteoporotic L4 compression fracture. 

Moderate remote benign osteoporotic L5 compression fracture without retropulsion.  Low signal is seen along the superior endplate which may reflect vertebral augmentation or sclerosis.

TECHNIQUE: 
Noncontrast chest CT was obtained. 


FINDINGS: 
There is mild cardiomegaly with notable biatrial involvement.  There is no pericardial effusion. 

There is calcification at the aortic valve and aortic root.  Coronary artery calcifications are seen.  Calcification of the mitral valve annulus is seen.  

There is a moderate-sized right pleural effusion and a small left pleural effusion. 


IMPRESSION: 
Mild cardiomegaly with notable biatrial involvement.

TECHNIQUE: 
Multiplanar, multisequence noncontrast brain MRI was performed 


FINDINGS: 
There are punctate foci of T2/FLAIR hyperintensity within the supratentorial bifrontal subcortical white matter, right greater than left.  This is nonspecific but may reflect the sequelae of migraines or minimal chronic microvascular ischemia.  There is no acute or early subacute infarct. 


IMPRESSION: 
Minimal bifrontal subcortical white matter signal change which is nonspecific but may reflect the sequelae of migraines or minimal chronic microvascular ischemia.  No acute infarct.

Technique: 
CT images of the chest were obtained before and after the administration of intravenous contrast.  Multiplanar reformatted images were provided. 

Findings: 
Heart: The heart is normal in size. There is no evidence of cardiac trauma. There is a mild to moderate pericardial effusion. There is no bowing of the intraventricular septum to suggest tamponade physiology. 
Lungs: Upper lobe predominant centrilobular emphysema. Flattening of the diaphragm is noted bilaterally, also consistent with emphysema. 

Impression:
Small to moderate pericardial effusion without evidence of cardiac tamponade. 
Upper lobe predominant centrilobular emphysema.

Technique: CT of the chest with and without IV contrast. Multiplanar reformats obtained.


Findings:
Heart: The heart is normal in size. There is a trace pericardial effusion. There are scattered coronary artery calcifications.
Lungs: Clear lungs. No pleural effusion.

Impression:
Normal size heart. Trace pericardial effusion. Scattered coronary artery calcifications. Clear lungs

TECHNIQUE:
Multiplanar, multisequence brain MRI was performed.

FINDINGS:
Patchy areas and scattered foci of T2/FLAIR hyperintensity are identified within the supratentorial subcortical, deep hemispheric, and periventricular white matter with notable bilateral posterior periventricular involvement. Involvement of the pontine white matter is also seen to a lesser extent. This is nonspecific but likely reflects moderate chronic microvascular ischemia. There is a remote posterior left cerebellar PICA branch infarct. There is no acute or early subacute infarct.

IMPRESSION:
Moderate chronic microvascular ischemia with a remote left PICA branch cerebellar infarct but no acute infarct.

Technique: CT of the Abdomen and Pelvis with IV and oral contrast.

Findings: Moderate calcific atherosclerosis of the abdominal aorta and common iliac arteries. Metallic stent in the proximal right main renal artery. 3.4 x 3.4 cm fusiform aneurysm of the infrarenal abdominal aorta. Sigmoid diverticulosis without evidence of acute diverticulitis.

Impression:
- Moderate calcific atherosclerosis of the abdominal aorta and common iliac arteries.
- Metallic stent in the proximal right main renal artery.
- 3.4 x 3.4 cm fusiform aneurysm of the infrarenal abdominal aorta.
- Sigmoid diverticulosis without evidence of acute diverticulitis.

Technique: Non contrast had CT was performed.

Findings: There is a chronic infarct in the right frontal, parietal,, and occipital lobes in a watershed distribution. There is no acute lobar infarct. There is no midline shift, hemorrhage, hydrocephalus, or herniation. There's diffuse cerebral volume loss and chronic small ischemic change. The skull is intact. The orbits are unremarkable.

Impression: Chronic right cerebral infarcts which appear to be in a water territory. No acute infarct or hemorrhage.  Consider CTA head and neck evaluation to rule out carotid stenosis.
