TECHNIQUE: 
CT of the abdomen and pelvis was performed with IV and oral contrast. 


FINDINGS: 
The liver demonstrates diffuse low attenuation relative to the spleen in keeping with diffuse fatty infiltration.  Minimal focal fatty sparing is seen adjacent to the gallbladder fossa inferiorly.  A 0.4 cm peripheral low-density focus is seen in the posterior right hepatic lobe in segment 6, in keeping with a cyst.  There is no suspicious enhancing hepatic lesion or evidence of cirrhosis.  There is patency of the portal and hepatic veins. 


IMPRESSION: 
Diffuse fatty infiltration of the liver with minimal focal fatty sparing adjacent to the gallbladder fossa. 

0.4 cm peripheral right hepatic cyst in segment 6.

Technique: Multiplanar MRI of the abdomen with and without intravenous contrast.

Findings:
Shrunken liver with lobulated contour, consistent with cirrhotic liver morphology. No drop of signal on in and out of phase imaging indicating no hepatic steatosis. No hepatic mass. 

The portal venous system is patent. There are multiple upper abdominal varices, prominent in the peri splenic space. There is a large splenorenal shunt as well with dilation of the left renal vein.

There is splenomegaly measuring up to 16.5 cm.

Trace ascites in the right paracolic gutter.

Impression:

Findings consistent with cirrhotic liver with clinically significant portal hypertension.

Technique: CT of the abdomen and pelvis performed with p.o. and IV contrast.  Multiplanar reformatted images provided.  

Findings:

Lung bases: The imaged lower lungs are clear.  The imaged portion of the heart is unremarkable.

Abdomen: Nodular contour of the liver is suggestive of cirrhosis.  Ill-defined approximately 4 cm hypodensity is seen at the hepatic dome near the hepatic veins which may be further evaluated with nonemergent MRI.  The main portal vein is patent.  Gallbladder is contracted around numerous gallstones.  There is no biliary ductal dilation.  The spleen is enlarged measuring 13.9 cm.  Adrenal glands appear normal.  The pancreas is unremarkable.  Kidneys enhance symmetrically.  There are several renal cortical cysts, largest at the midpole left kidney measuring up to 2.5 cm.  The abdominal aorta is mildly calcified and normal in course and caliber.  Small hiatal hernia.  Stomach otherwise unremarkable.  Small bowel and large bowel are unremarkable without signs of inflammation or bowel obstruction.  The appendix is normal.  Contrast is seen to the level of the colon.  There is no free air or free fluid.  The urinary bladder is abnormally thickened with perivesical fat stranding concerning for cystitis.  Prostate normal in size.  There is no concerning lytic or blastic bone lesion.  No fracture.  Degenerative disc disease most pronounced at L4-5 level.

Impression: 
1.  Cirrhotic liver morphology with ill-defined 4 cm hypodensity at the hepatic dome which can be further evaluated with nonemergent MRI of the liver.  Splenomegaly, no ascites, patent main portal vein.

2.  Cholelithiasis without evidence of cholecystitis.

3.  Abnormal thickening of the urinary bladder wall with adjacent fat stranding concerning for cystitis.

4.  Small hiatal hernia.

Technique:  A multi-planar, multi-sequence MRI of the brain was performed without IV contrast

Findings:  Encephalomacia changes are noted in the left frontal, parietal and temporal lobes associated with volume loss and no restricted diffusion.  On the gradient sequence, there is suseptibility artifact in the left temporoparietal region which likely represents hemosiderin deposition related prior microhemorrhage associated with the remote infarcts.  There is also increased cortically based T1 signal in this region consistent with laminar necrosis.  

Impression:  Remote left frontal and temporoparietal infarcts.

TECHNIQUE: Axial CT of the abdomen and pelvis with IV and oral contrast with coronal and sagital reformats. Delayed axial CT images through the pelvis also obtained. 

FINDINGS:
Lung bases: Left lower lobe cyst measuring 2.1 x. 2.9cm. No pleural effusion.
Liver: Normal in size and attenuation. 5mm cyst at the right hepatic lobe near the dome. 
Gallbladder and bile ducts: 15mm x 13mm gallstone near the neck of the gallbladder. No gallbladder wall thickening or pericholecystic fluid. No biliary dilation.
Spleen: Normal in size.
Pancreas: The pancreas is mildly atrophic. No peripancreatic fluid.
Adrenal Glands: Unremarkable.
Kidneys and ureters: No hydronephrosis or hydroureter. 9mm exophytic cyst at the mid portion of the right kidney. 7mm cyst at the inferior portion of the left kidney. 7mm cyst at the mid portion of the left kidney. Tiny 2mm cyst at the mid portion of the right kidney. Possible 3mm stone at the lower portion of the right kidney.
Bowel: No bowel obstruction. Appendix is normal. Diverticulosis without diverticulitis. 
Bladder: Unremarkable. 
Reproductive organs: Unremarkable.

Peritoneum: No free air or free fluid.
Lymph nodes: No enlarged lymph nodes
Vasculature: Abdominal aorta normal in caliber and tortuous.  Atherosclerotic vascular calcifications in the lower thoracic aorta and the abdominal aorta. Pelvic phlebolith.
Abdominal wall: Bilateral fat containing inguinal hernias. 

Bone: L1 vertebral compression fracture with approximately 30% loss of height anteriorly. Degenerative changes at the lumbar spine with osteophyte formation. Subchondral cystic change at the left acetabulum. Spinal scoliosis. 

IMPRESSION:
1. Gallstone measuring up to 15mm near the neck of the gallbladder. No evidence of acute cholecystitis.
2. L1 vertebral compression fracture.
3. Bilateral renal cysts.
4. Diverticulosis without diverticulitis. 
5. Left lower lobe pulmonary cyst. 
6. Atherosclerotic vascular calcifications of the aorta.

TECHNIQUE: Axial CT without intravenous contrast of the Chest.

FINDINGS: 
No focal lung consolidation. No pneumothorax or pleural effusion. 

No suspicious pulmonary nodule.
In the visualized Abdomen, there is a Segment 2 cyst measuring 4.1 x 4.0 cm (Axial, Image 87). Additionally, there is a bilobed Segment 2 cyst measuring 2.7 x 2.5 cm (Axial, Image 72) and 1.8 x 1.6 cm Axial, Image 72).  There is a by Segment 4a cyst measuring 2.1 x 1.6 cm (Axial, Image 83). The contents of the cysts measure < 20 Hounsfield units, suggesting simple fluid. There are no calcifications or mural thrombi within the cysts. The liver is normal in size and contour.

IMPRESSION:
1. Multiple simple cysts within the liver, as described above. Normal size and contour of the liver.
2. No acute pulmonary pathology.

Technique:
CT chest without intravenous contrast with multiplanar reformats. 

Findings:

Cardiomegaly. Mitral valve replacement. No pericardial effusion. Midline sternotomy. 

Cholecystectomy. 

Impression:

Cardiomegaly.

Technique: Non-contrast CT of the chest, abdomen and pelvis.

Findings: Irregular contour of the liver consistent with cirrhosis. Large volume ascites. No discrete varicosities. Borderline splenomegaly.

Impression:
Findings consistent with cirrhosis and large volume ascites.

TECHNIQUE: 
Contiguous axial CT sections were acquired through the head without the use of IV contrast. 

FINDINGS: 
There is mild patchy periventricular diminished attenuation, which may reflect mild chronic microvascular ischemia.  There is a small remote lacunar infarct in the left caudate head.  The gray-white differentiation is maintained without recent transcortical infarct. 

IMPRESSION: 
Mild chronic microvascular ischemia with a small remote lacunar infarct within the left caudate head but no recent transcortical infarct.

TECHNIQUE: CT head obtained with no IV contrast. Multiplanar reformats performed. 

FINDINGS:  
Low-density encephalomalacia identified at the right inferior frontal lobe, right insula, external capsule and globus pallidus, superior right temporal lobe measuring 6.1 x 3.4 cm. There is mild ex vacuo enlargement of the right frontal horn and right temporal horn. There is no hemorrhage and no evidence for acute infarct.

IMPRESSION:

1. Old infarct at the right MCA territory, superior division. No acute infarct or hemorrhage.

Technique: CT of the abdomen and pelvis with IV contrast. Multiplanar reformats obtained.


Findings:
Kidney: Mild to moderate left renal hydronephrosis. No obstructing renal calculi or masses.  Symmetric enhancement. No solid enhancing renal masses. No right hydronephrosis. 
Urinary bladder: Unremarkable urinary bladder. 
 
Impression:
Mild to moderate left renal hydronephrosis. No evidence of obstructing renal cacluli or masses. No right hydronephrosis.

TECHNIQUE: Axial CT of the abdomen and pelvis without IV or oral contrast with sagittal reformats

FINDINGS:
Lung bases: Clear. No pleural effusion.
Liver: Normal in size and attenuation. No focal lesion. 
Gallbladder and bile ducts: Gallbladder is unremarkable. No biliary dilation.
Spleen: Normal in size.
Pancreas: Unremarkable.
Adrenal Glands: Unremarkable.
Kidneys and ureters: Bilateral renal stones. Two stones at the mid portion of the left kidney measuring up to 3mm.  5mm inferior right renal calculus. No hydronephrosis or hydroureter. Exophytic left renal cyst measuring up to 16mm at the mid portion of the left kidney. 
Bowel: No bowel obstruction. Appendix is normal.
Bladder: Unremarkable. 
Reproductive organs: Prostatic calcifications.

Peritoneum: No free air or free fluid.
Lymph nodes: No enlarged lymph nodes
Vasculature: Abdominal aorta normal in caliber. Atherosclerotic vascular calcifications throughout the abdominal aorta and bilateral iliac arteries and branches. Phleboliths in the pelvis.
Abdominal wall: Small fat containing left inguinal hernia.

Bone: No acute osseous abnormality. Degenerative changes most pronounced at the L5-S1 level with disc space narrowing and osteophyte formation. Mild degenerative changes at the sacroiliac joints. Bone cyst at the right sacrum. 

IMPRESSION:
1. Bilateral non-obstructing renal stones measuring up to 5mm. 
2. Atherosclerotic vascular calcifications.
3. Degenerative changes of the spine.

TECHNIQUE: 
Scout radiograph of the chest was obtained followed by contrast-enhanced CT of the chest. 


FINDINGS: 
The heart is at the upper limits of normal for size.  There is no cardiac chamber enlargement.  There is no pericardial effusion. 

Coronary artery calcifications are present. 


IMPRESSION: 
The heart is at the upper limits of normal for size.

TECHNIQUE: Axial CT of the abdomen and pelvis without and with IV contrast with multiplanar reformats. Delayed images of the abdomen and pelvis were also obtained.

FINDINGS:
Scattered bilateral renal cysts measuring up to 6mm in the right kidney and up to 7mm in the left kidney. 

IMPRESSION:
Scattered subcentimeter bilateral renal cysts, which are too small to characterize.

TECHNIQUE: Axial CT of the abdomen and pelvis with IV and oral contrast with sagittal reformats. 

FINDINGS:
Lung bases: Clear. No pleural effusion.
Liver: Normal in size and attenuation. No focal lesion. 
Gallbladder and bile ducts: Gallbladder is unremarkable. No biliary dilation.
Spleen: Normal in size.
Pancreas: The pancreas is normal. No peripancreatic fluid.
Adrenal Glands: Unremarkable.
Kidneys and ureters: There is a 12 mm renal cyst at the mid portion of the left kidney. There is another subcentimeter cyst at the superior portion of the left kidney. Moderate left hydroureteronephrosis with left proximal and mid ureter measuring up to 15 mm.  Tiny 3 mm calcification at the left kidney may represent a small stone. 12 mm calcification in the region of the left distal ureter may represent a stone vs. phlebolith.
Bowel: No bowel obstruction. Appendix is normal.
Bladder: Unremarkable. 
Reproductive organs: Heterogeneously hypodense lesions within and adjacent to the uterus. Left sided lesion measures 10.3 x 11.3 cm, which is in the region of the left distal ureter. Right sided lesion in the region of the lower uterine segment measures 8.9 x 5.9 cm.  The right ovary appears normal. The left ovary may be located adjacent to the left adnexal/uterine lesion.

Peritoneum: No free air or free fluid.
Lymph nodes: No enlarged lymph nodes
Vasculature: Abdominal aorta normal in caliber.  Phleboliths in the pelvis.
Abdominal wall: No hernia.

Bone: No acute osseous abnormality. Degenerative changes at the L5-S1 level.

IMPRESSION:
1. Moderate left hydroureteronephrosis with possible 12 mm urinary stone vs. phlebolith in the region of the left distal ureter. Tiny left intrarenal stone also noted. 
2. Large pelvic lesions measuring up to 11.3 cm within and adjacent to the uterus favored to represent uterine fibroids. Superimposed ovarian cyst not entirely excluded. Further evaluation may be performed with ultrasound of the pelvis. 
3. Left renal cysts measuring up to 2 cm.
4. Degenerative changes at the lower lumbar spine.

Technique: Axial CT images of the abdomen and pelvis were obtained after the administration of intravenous contrast in the venous and delayed phases. Multiplanar reformats were obtained. 

FINDINGS:

Multiple renal cysts in the left kidney, the largest measuring 1.1 x 1.3 cm and located in the interpolar region. 

No hydronephrosis, renal stones or perinephric fat stranding in the bilateral kidneys. 

Left adnexal cyst measuring 2.9 x 3.3 cm.  No right adnexal mass. Normal uterus. 

Partial visualization of T10 severe compression fracture.

IMPRESSION: 

1.	Multiple left renal cysts as described above. 
2.	Left adnexal cyst measuring up 3.3 cm. 
3.	Partial visualization of T10 compression fracture, of uncertain chronicity, but favored to be chronic.

Technique: CT images of the abdomen and pelvis were obtained with IV contrast. Multiplanar reformats obtained.


Urinary bladder: Mildly thickened urinary bladder wall without significant adjacent inflammatory stranding.
Peritoneum: Small volume pelvic ascites measuring approximately 5.7 x 2.0 x 4.5cm located between the bladder and rectum.


Impression:
Small volume pelvic ascites measuring approximately 5.7 x 2.0 x 4.5 cm.
Mildly thickened urinary bladder wall. Correlate with UA for cystitis.

Technique: CT images of the abdomen were obtained with and without IV contrast with multiple phases obtained. Multiplanar reformats obtained.


Findings:
Liver: The liver is enlarged measuring up to 24cm in craniocaudal dimension. The liver parenchyma demonstrates diffusely low attenuation (HU under 10) compatible with fatty infiltration. No liver masses.
Spleen: Normal sized spleen.


Impression:
Hepatomegaly. Hepatic steatosis.

Technique:  Pre- and postcontrast CT of the abdomen and pelvis, performed in the noncontrast, portal venous, and delayed phases.

Findings:
There is a 2.2 cm rim-calcified gallstone in the neck of the gallbladder.  The gallbladder is not dilated.  No evidence for pericholecystic inflammation or abnormal gallbladder wall thickening.

The common bile duct is within normal limits in size, measuring 6 mm in diameter.  No intrahepatic bile duct dilatation.

Impression:  Cholelithiasis without evidence for acute cholecystitis.

Technique: Multiplanar, multisequence MRI of the lumbar spine without IV contrast

Findings:
There is minimal grade 1 anterolisthesis of L3 with associated disc bulge and moderate to severe spinal canal narrowing at the level of L3-4. There is moderate bilateral facet hypertrophy at this level.  There is also bilateral facet hypertrophy at this level.

There is also multilevel discogenic disc disease and multilevel bilateral facet hypertrophy involving the lumbar and visualized lower thoracic spine.

Impression:
Minimal grade 1 anterolisthesis of L4 with associated disc bulge and facet hypertrophy resulting in moderate to severe spinal canal narrowing at this level and moderate bilateral neuroforaminal narrowing at this level.

Otherwise, multilevel discogenic disease and multilevel bilateral facet hypertrophy.

Technique: Multidetector CT images of the abdomen and pelvis were obtained without intravenous contrast. Sagittal and coronal reformatted images were submitted for review.

Findings
There is moderate-to-severe left-sided hydroureteronephrosis to the level of a distal 1.0 x 0.6 cm ureteral calculus. There is associated slight perinephric stranding. There are scattered additional non-obstructive punctate left renal calculi, the largest measuring 0.2 cm.  No left-sided renal parenchyma masses or focal fluid perinephric fluid collections within the limitations of unenhanced technique.

Incidental note is made of non-obstructive right-sided renal calculi, the largest of which is 0.5 cm within the right renal pelvis. There is no right-sided hydronephrosis. 

Impression:
Moderate to severe left-sided hydroureteronephrosis to the level of a distal ureteral calculus.
Non-obstructive bilateral renal calculi.

TECHNIQUE: Noncontrast CT of the abdomen and pelvis with multiplanar reformats.

Impression:
1. Nonobstructing bilateral renal calculi.

3. Postoperative changes of sleeve gastrectomy.
